const ALL_CARDS = [
  {id:1,number:"Illustration 1",subtopic:"Penal Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-024] (Ill. 1) · cf. Huntington v Attrill",question:"X incurs a £100 penalty for infringing a foreign law prohibiting the sale of spirits. An official of the foreign government brings an action in the English High Court to recover the £100. Can the claim be maintained?",answer:"No. The claim cannot be maintained. This is a foreign penal law — the penalty was imposed by a foreign state for breach of its public law. English courts will not enforce foreign penal laws.",keyPrinciple:"Foreign penal laws are unenforceable in English courts."},
  {id:2,number:"Illustration 2",subtopic:"Penal Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-024] (Ill. 2) · cf. Huntington v Attrill",question:"Under New York law, a director who signs false certificates becomes personally liable for the debts of the corporation. X, a director of a New York company, is in England. A, a creditor, brings an action against X for a debt due from the company. Is X likely to be liable?",answer:"It appears that X may be made liable. This is not a penal law but a civil liability imposed on a director for misconduct. The action is by a private creditor, not the state, so the penal law bar does not apply.",keyPrinciple:"A private creditor's action under foreign law is not 'penal' — the state must be the one seeking to punish."},
  {id:3,number:"Illustration 3",subtopic:"Penal Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-024] (Ill. 3) · Huntington v Attrill",question:"Under New York law, a director who signs false certificates becomes personally liable for the debts of the corporation. X, a director of a New York company, is in England. A, a creditor, has already recovered judgment against X in the court of New York for the debt, and now brings an action on that judgment in England. Is the judgment enforceable?",answer:"It appears that the judgment is enforceable. Once a foreign court has given judgment, the action in England is on the judgment itself (a debt), not on the original foreign law. The penal nature of the original law is spent.",keyPrinciple:"A judgment obtained in a foreign court converts the claim into an enforceable debt, even if the underlying law was penal."},
  {id:4,number:"Illustration 4",subtopic:"Penal Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-024] (Ill. 4) · Banco de Vizcaya v Don Alfonso de Borbon y Austria",question:"The King of Spain deposits securities with Westminster Bank in London to the order of a Spanish bank as his agents. A decree by the Constituent Cortes of Spain declares the King guilty of treason, and orders all his assets to be seized for the benefit of the Spanish State. Spain asks the English court to order delivery of the securities to a nominee of the Spanish Republic. Will the court comply?",answer:"No. The court will not order delivery. The Spanish decree is penal in nature — it punishes the King and transfers his assets to the State as a form of confiscation. English courts will not enforce such a foreign penal/confiscatory decree.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign state cannot use English courts to enforce a confiscatory decree that is penal in character."},
  {id:5,number:"Illustration 5",subtopic:"Penal Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-025] (Ill. 5) · US v Inkley",question:"X, a British subject, is charged with fraud in the United States and released on bail on condition he enters into an 'appearance bond' of $48,000. He returns to England and does not go back to the US. The United States Government obtains a civil judgment on the bond in a federal court in Florida. Can that judgment be enforced in England?",answer:"No. The Florida judgment cannot be enforced in England. The purpose of the appearance bond was to secure X's presence for criminal prosecution and to exact pecuniary penalties for non-attendance. This makes it penal in nature — it serves the state's prosecutorial interest, not a private compensatory one.",keyPrinciple:"A bond whose purpose is to secure criminal prosecution is penal, even if framed as a civil judgment."},
  {id:6,number:"Illustration 6",subtopic:"Penal Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-025] (Ill. 6) · United States v Abacha",question:"X, Head of State of Ruritania, flees to the United States where he deposits the proceeds of corrupt activities. The United States Government commences civil proceedings for forfeiture of funds involved in money-laundering. A freezing injunction is sought in England in aid of the US proceedings. Should it be granted?",answer:"No. Any freezing injunction is discharged. A US forfeiture judgment would be unenforceable in England as it would amount to enforcing a foreign penal law — the basis of the proceedings is alleged money-laundering, which is punitive and not compensatory.",keyPrinciple:"Civil forfeiture proceedings rooted in criminal conduct (money-laundering) are penal, not compensatory, and cannot be enforced in England."},
  {id:7,number:"Illustration 7",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-026] (Ill. 7) · Municipal Council of Sydney v Bull",question:"Under an Act of Parliament of New South Wales, the municipality of Sydney is authorised to carry out improvements in the city and to charge the cost to the owners of affected property. X, an owner of affected property, is resident in England. The council brings an action against X for the sum due under the NSW Act. Can the claim be maintained?",answer:"No. The claim cannot be maintained. This is a foreign revenue law — a statutory charge imposed by a foreign public authority. English courts will not directly enforce foreign revenue laws.",keyPrinciple:"Foreign revenue laws (statutory charges/taxes imposed by foreign public bodies) cannot be enforced in English courts."},
  {id:8,number:"Illustration 8",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-026] (Ill. 8) · Cross-Border Insolvency Regs (SI 2006/1030) reversing Government of India v Taylor",question:"A company registered in England carries on business in India and becomes liable to Indian capital gains tax. The company is wound up in England and the Indian Government lodges a claim in respect of the unpaid tax. Can the Indian Government prove the tax debt in the English liquidation?",answer:"No. The revenue rule prevents the Indian Government from proving in the English liquidation for foreign tax. The revenue rule is not displaced merely because the company is incorporated in England.",keyPrinciple:"The foreign revenue rule applies regardless of where a company is incorporated — the claim is still for a foreign tax."},
  {id:9,number:"Illustration 9",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-026] (Ill. 9) · Re Visser; cf. Re State of Norway's Application",question:"X is the English personal representative of a Dutch national domiciled at his death in Holland. Under Dutch law, duties are payable in respect of his estate. The Queen of Holland brings an action against X in England to recover the sum due. Can the action succeed?",answer:"It appears that the action fails. Although in Re Visser the action succeeded on characterisation grounds, the better view following Re State of Norway's Application is that a foreign state's claim to recover tax through English proceedings is barred by the revenue rule.",keyPrinciple:"The revenue rule may not bar all foreign state tax claims — characterisation of the claim matters."},
  {id:10,number:"Illustration 10",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-026] (Ill. 10) · Rossano v Manufacturers' Life Insurance Co",question:"X Co is a Canadian insurance company with a branch in Egypt which issues policies to A, under which money is due to A. X Co is served with a garnishee order by the Egyptian revenue authorities in respect of tax allegedly due by A to the Egyptian Government. Does the garnishee order afford X Co a defence in English proceedings to recover the debt?",answer:"No. Recognition of the garnishee order would constitute indirect enforcement of a foreign revenue law. English courts will not give effect to foreign revenue claims even indirectly through garnishee or similar orders.",keyPrinciple:"Indirect enforcement of foreign revenue laws is equally prohibited — form does not matter, substance does."},
  {id:11,number:"Illustration 11",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-026] (Ill. 11) · cf. Jones v Borland",question:"T dies domiciled in South Africa leaving property in England and South Africa. A is his South African executor and X is his English executor. After payment of United Kingdom duties and debts there is a surplus in A's hands. There are insufficient assets in South Africa to pay South African death duties. Must A remit the surplus assets directly to the legatees or to X?",answer:"It is A's duty to remit the surplus to the South African Government, not to X. The South African Government cannot enforce its claim for duties directly in England, but A as South African executor is bound by South African law to pay and must remit accordingly.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign state cannot directly enforce revenue claims in England, but a local executor remains bound by the foreign law obligations."},
  {id:12,number:"Illustration 12",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-027] (Ill. 12) · cf. Scottish National Orchestra Society Ltd v Thomson's Executor",question:"T dies domiciled in South Africa leaving property in England and South Africa. A is his South African executor and X is his English executor. After payment of United Kingdom duties and debts there is a surplus in A's hands. There are insufficient assets in South Africa to pay South African death duties. Some of the legatees reside in South Africa. If those legatees are paid their legacies, will they be liable to South Africa for duty on the whole estate?",answer:"Yes — legatees resident in South Africa who receive their legacies will be answerable to the South African Government to the extent of those legacies for duty on the whole estate. A must remit the surplus assets to X accordingly.",keyPrinciple:"Legatees present in a foreign jurisdiction remain personally bound by that state's revenue laws on sums they receive."},
  {id:13,number:"Illustration 13",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-027] (Ill. 13) · Brokaw v Seatrain UK Ltd",question:"X and Y, United States citizens, send some furniture by sea to Z, their son-in-law living in London. While the ship is on the high seas the United States Treasury serves a notice of levy on the shipowners in respect of unpaid tax demanding surrender of all property belonging to X and Y. Can Z claim the furniture from the shipowners?",answer:"Yes — Z is entitled to claim the furniture. To give effect to the US Treasury's levy would be indirect enforcement of a foreign revenue law. The property is not reduced into the possession of the United States Treasury, and English courts will not assist foreign states in collecting taxes, even against third-party property holders.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign state's tax levy cannot be enforced indirectly through third parties holding goods in England."},
  {id:14,number:"Illustration 14",subtopic:"Revenue Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-027] (Ill. 14) · Skatteforvaltningen v Solo Capital Partners LLP",question:"The Danish national tax authority brings an action in England against X for the return of £1.5 billion in tax refunds which X had allegedly obtained by misrepresentation. Although framed as a private law claim for misrepresentation, the central interest in bringing the claim is the recovery of tax. Is this claim barred by the revenue rule?",answer:"Yes — the claim is dismissed. Although framed as misrepresentation, the central interest in bringing the claim is the recovery of tax. It is therefore characterised as a revenue claim and dismissed.",keyPrinciple:"Courts look at the substance of a claim, not just its legal form — a tax recovery claim disguised as misrepresentation is still a revenue claim."},
  {id:15,number:"Illustration 15",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-028] (Ill. 15) · cf. Don Alonso v Cornero; cf. Princess Paley Olga v Weisz",question:"The government of a foreign State passes a decree expropriating certain jewellery belonging to X which is situated within that State at the time of the decree. X brings the jewellery to London, where it is claimed by the foreign government. Will the claim succeed?",answer:"It appears that the claim fails. Although the situs rule may give effect to the foreign expropriation decree in some cases, English courts are reluctant to enforce foreign public/governmental acts of expropriation, particularly where it would amount to enforcing a foreign public law.",keyPrinciple:"Foreign expropriation decrees are treated as public law acts and generally will not be enforced by English courts."},
  {id:16,number:"Illustration 16",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-028] (Ill. 16) · Suggested by British Nylon Spinners Ltd v ICI Ltd",question:"In furtherance of their agreement for the establishment of an international monopoly, an English company is assigned certain American patents by an American corporation. The United States Government claims the cancellation of the assignment under the Sherman Anti-Trust Act. Can the US government succeed?",answer:"No — the claim fails. The Sherman Anti-Trust Act is a US public/regulatory law. English courts will not enforce foreign public regulatory laws that are essentially governmental in character and have no private law analogue.",keyPrinciple:"Foreign regulatory or anti-trust laws are public laws that English courts will not enforce."},
  {id:17,number:"Illustration 17",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-028] (Ill. 17) · cf. King of Italy v De Medici",question:"X brings manuscripts to England from Italy despite a decree of the Italian Government forbidding their export. The decree also grants the Italian State a first option to purchase the manuscripts. X seeks to dispose of them to Y in London, and the Italian Government claims an injunction to prevent such a disposal. Will the court grant it?",answer:"It appears that the court will not grant an injunction. The Italian decree is a public law instrument of the Italian state. English courts will not enforce foreign public laws even in the form of injunctive relief.",keyPrinciple:"The public law bar applies regardless of remedy sought — injunctions to enforce foreign public laws are equally refused."},
  {id:18,number:"Illustration 18",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-028] (Ill. 18) · Att-Gen of New Zealand v Ortiz",question:"X brings an ancient Maori carving from New Zealand to England in contravention of a New Zealand statute which provides that historic articles illegally exported shall be forfeited to the Crown. The New Zealand Government brings an action in England for the return and delivery up of the carving. Will it succeed?",answer:"No — the action fails. First, the Crown has not acquired title under New Zealand law. Second (per Lord Denning MR), the NZ statute is a public law. Third (per Ackner and O'Connor LJJ), it is a penal law. Either way, English courts will not enforce it.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign statute forfeiting cultural property to the state is both a public law and a penal law — doubly unenforceable in England."},
  {id:19,number:"Illustration 19",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-028] (Ill. 19) · Islamic Republic of Iran v Barakat Galleries Ltd",question:"Ancient artefacts are found buried in Iran and illegally exported and brought to London. Under Iranian law, artefacts in the ground belong to the State. Can Iran sue to recover them in England?",answer:"Yes — Iran may sue to recover them. Iran's claim is based on vested title (ownership), not enforcement of a penal or public law. A state asserting property rights it already holds under its own law is not barred by the public or penal law rules.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign state asserting pre-existing property rights (vested title) is not barred — this is a property claim, not enforcement of a public/penal law."},
  {id:20,number:"Illustration 20",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-028] (Ill. 20) · Based on facts of Lepage v San Paulo Copper Estates Ltd (Dicey view: wrongly decided)",question:"X is a German national resident in France. A state of war exists between Germany and France. The French custodian of enemy property, duly appointed under French law, is entitled to control all of X's property and claims payment to him of a dividend on shares held by X in an English company. Will the English court order payment?",answer:"It appears that the court will not order payment. The French enemy property custodian scheme is a public law instrument tied to a state of war. English courts will not give effect to foreign public law acts of this kind, especially where they operate against private property rights.",keyPrinciple:"Enemy property legislation is a public law measure that English courts will not enforce on behalf of a foreign state."},
  {id:21,number:"Illustration 21",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-028] (Ill. 21) · Att-Gen (UK) v Heinemann Publishers Australia Pty Ltd",question:"X is a former member of the British security services and Y is a publisher. X writes a book about his experiences and proposes to publish it in Australia. The United Kingdom Government seeks an injunction in England against X and Y to restrain publication in Australia. Will an injunction be granted?",answer:"No — an injunction is refused. The purpose of the UK Government's action is to enforce a governmental interest (protecting the efficiency of its security service). English courts will not grant injunctions to enforce governmental/public law interests even of the forum state when directed at protecting state functions rather than private rights.",keyPrinciple:"Even domestic governmental interests framed as injunction claims may be refused if they amount to enforcement of public (not private) law interests."},
  {id:22,number:"Illustration 22",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-029] (Ill. 22) · Camdex International Ltd v Bank of Zambia (No.2)",question:"A & Co obtains a judgment in England against the Bank of Zambia. It seeks a garnishee order in respect of funds held in London by X & Co, the biggest copper producer in Zambia. Under Zambian exchange control law, X & Co is bound to transfer a proportion of its funds to the Bank of Zambia. Is the garnishee order set aside?",answer:"Yes — the garnishee order is set aside. To enforce it would require giving effect to Zambian public law (exchange control legislation). Even if the obligation of X & Co to the Bank of Zambia were a debt (which it is not), attachment of such a debt would be indirect enforcement of Zambian public law.",keyPrinciple:"Exchange control laws are public laws — enforcement of them, even indirectly via garnishee, is barred."},
  {id:23,number:"Illustration 23",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-029] (Ill. 23) · cf. United States Securities and Exchange Commission v Manterfield",question:"The United States Securities and Exchange Commission brings proceedings in the United States District Court alleging that X and Y fraudulently induced Taiwanese investors to invest approximately $34 million in a fund and misappropriated millions of dollars. The SEC applies to the English court for interim freezing orders in support of its proceedings. Should the freezing orders be upheld?",answer:"Yes — the freezing orders are upheld. The US proceedings are for disgorgement of the proceeds of fraud and their return to the investors, and consequently a judgment in those proceedings would not be a penal judgment or otherwise unenforceable under Rule 20(1).",keyPrinciple:"Disgorgement of fraud proceeds returned to victims is compensatory, not penal — English courts can assist such foreign proceedings."},
  {id:24,number:"Illustration 24",subtopic:"Other Public Laws",tags:["topic:Exclusion of Foreign Law","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 20 [8-029] (Ill. 24) · Mbasogo v Logo Ltd",question:"The head of State of a mineral-rich African republic and the State itself bring proceedings against X and Y alleging conspiracy to overthrow the government and seize power by means of a coup. They claim damages for commercial losses, investigation costs, detaining and prosecuting suspects, and the head of state's personal anxiety, distress and disruption to his personal life. Are the claims justiciable?",answer:"No — the claims are not justiciable. They are in respect of losses suffered by the governing body of a State and amount to the exercise of sovereign power within the jurisdiction of the English court. Such claims are non-justiciable as they involve the court adjudicating on acts of a foreign sovereign state.",keyPrinciple:"Claims that amount to a foreign state exercising sovereign power before English courts are non-justiciable — courts will not adjudicate on sovereign acts."},
  {id:25,number:"Rome II – Art 1(2)",subtopic:"Scope",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 1(2)",question:"Rome II does not apply to all non-contractual obligations. Name the seven categories excluded from its scope.",answer:"Art 1(2) excludes: (a) family relationships and maintenance; (b) matrimonial property regimes, comparable relationships, wills and succession; (c) bills of exchange and negotiable instruments; (d) company law obligations (creation, capacity, internal organisation, officers' personal liability, auditors' liability); (e) trust relationships between settlors, trustees and beneficiaries; (f) nuclear damage; (g) violations of privacy and personality rights, including defamation.",keyPrinciple:"Rome II excludes obligations governed by specialised regimes — family, company, trusts, negotiable instruments, nuclear, and privacy/defamation."},
  {id:26,number:"Rome II – Art 1(2)(g)",subtopic:"Scope",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 1(2)(g)",question:"A newspaper publishes an article in England alleged to defame C, a French national. C sues in England. Which Rome II exclusion applies, and what is the result?",answer:"Art 1(2)(g) excludes non-contractual obligations arising out of violations of privacy and rights relating to personality, including defamation. Rome II does not govern. The court applies common law choice of law rules for defamation instead.",keyPrinciple:"Defamation and privacy fall entirely outside Rome II — a significant practical gap in media and personality rights litigation."},
  {id:27,number:"Rome II – Art 2",subtopic:"Scope",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 2",question:"Rome II refers to 'damage' throughout. How does it define 'damage', and does it apply only to obligations that have already arisen?",answer:"Art 2(1) defines damage broadly to cover any consequence arising out of tort/delict, unjust enrichment, negotiorum gestio or culpa in contrahendo. Arts 2(2)-(3) confirm Rome II applies also to non-contractual obligations that are likely to arise — including likely damage and likely events giving rise to damage.",keyPrinciple:"Rome II applies prospectively as well as retrospectively — it covers likely damage, not just damage that has already occurred."},
  {id:28,number:"Rome II – Art 3",subtopic:"Universal application",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 3",question:"Must an English court apply the law designated by Rome II even if it is not the law of a Rome II state?",answer:"Yes. Art 3 provides for universal application — the law specified by Rome II shall be applied whether or not it is the law of the UK or a Member State. Rome II can therefore designate the law of any country in the world.",keyPrinciple:"Rome II operates on a universal basis — it can designate any country's law, not just EU/UK law."},
  {id:29,number:"Rome II – Art 4(1)",subtopic:"General tort rule",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 4(1)",question:"What is the general choice of law rule for tort under Rome II, and what connecting factor does it use?",answer:"Art 4(1): the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation arising out of a tort/delict is the law of the country in which the damage occurs (lex loci damni), irrespective of where the event giving rise to the damage occurred and irrespective of where any indirect consequences occur.",keyPrinciple:"Art 4(1) focuses on direct damage — lex loci damni — not the place of the act or where consequential loss is felt."},
  {id:30,number:"Rome II – Art 4(1) scenario",subtopic:"General tort rule",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 4(1)",question:"A driver negligently causes a road accident in Belgium. The victim, domiciled in England, suffers physical injuries in Belgium but loses earnings in England. Neither party shares habitual residence. Which law governs?",answer:"Art 4(1) applies — Belgian law governs, as that is where the direct damage (physical injury) occurred. The loss of earnings in England are indirect consequences and are disregarded for the purposes of Art 4(1).",keyPrinciple:"Indirect or consequential loss felt in the forum is irrelevant — Art 4(1) looks to where direct damage was sustained."},
  {id:31,number:"Rome II – Art 4(2)",subtopic:"General tort rule",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 4(2)",question:"When does the common habitual residence exception displace the general tort choice of law rule under Rome II, and what law applies instead?",answer:"Art 4(2): where both the person claimed to be liable and the person sustaining damage have their habitual residence in the same country at the time the damage occurs, the law of that country applies instead of the lex loci damni.",keyPrinciple:"Common habitual residence at the time of damage trumps lex loci damni under Art 4(2)."},
  {id:32,number:"Rome II – Art 4(2) scenario",subtopic:"General tort rule",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 4(2)",question:"A and B are both habitually resident in England. While on holiday together in Spain, A negligently injures B in a road accident. What law governs the tort claim?",answer:"Art 4(2) applies — both parties are habitually resident in England at the time the damage occurs. English law governs, displacing the Spanish lex loci damni under Art 4(1).",keyPrinciple:"Art 4(2) applies where both parties share habitual residence regardless of where the tort occurred."},
  {id:33,number:"Rome II – Art 4(3)",subtopic:"General tort rule",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 4(3)",question:"What is the escape clause for the general tort choice of law rule under Rome II, when can it displace the primary rules, and what example does the article give of a closer connection?",answer:"Art 4(3): where it is clear from all the circumstances that the tort is manifestly more closely connected with a country other than that indicated in Arts 4(1) or 4(2), the law of that other country applies. The article gives as an example a pre-existing relationship between the parties — such as a contract — that is closely connected with the tort.",keyPrinciple:"Art 4(3) is a genuine but high-threshold escape clause — 'manifestly more closely connected' requires compelling circumstances beyond a single connecting factor."},
  {id:34,number:"Rome II – Art 4(3) scenario",subtopic:"General tort rule",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 4(3)",question:"A (English) and B (French) enter into a contract governed by French law. In performing the contract, A negligently causes damage to B in England. B is habitually resident in France, A in England. The primary choice of law rules point to different laws. Can the escape clause resolve this?",answer:"Art 4(1) points to English law (place of damage). Art 4(2) does not apply (different habitual residences). Under Art 4(3), the pre-existing French-law contract closely connected with the tort may make it manifestly more closely connected with France — French law could apply under the escape clause.",keyPrinciple:"A pre-existing contractual relationship governed by a particular law is the paradigm case for the escape clause displacing the lex loci damni."},
  {id:35,number:"Rome II – Art 5",subtopic:"Product liability",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 5",question:"Describe the cascade of connecting factors for product liability under Rome II and the foreseeability proviso.",answer:"Art 5(1) establishes a cascade: (a) law of the country where the person sustaining damage had habitual residence when damage occurred, if the product was marketed there; failing that, (b) law of the country where the product was acquired, if marketed there; failing that, (c) law of the country where the damage occurred, if marketed there. However, if the person claimed to be liable could not reasonably foresee marketing in the designated country, the law of their habitual residence applies instead.",keyPrinciple:"Art 5 uses a victim-protective cascade but includes a foreseeability proviso protecting defendants from laws of countries where they did not market the product."},
  {id:36,number:"Rome II – Art 5 scenario",subtopic:"Product liability",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 5",question:"C, habitually resident in Australia, buys a product in England (where it is marketed) and is injured by it in France. The manufacturer is habitually resident in Germany. Which law governs the product liability claim?",answer:"Art 5(1)(a) fails — product not marketed in Australia (C's habitual residence). Art 5(1)(b) applies — the product was acquired in England and was marketed there. English law governs, subject to the foreseeability proviso (the manufacturer could reasonably foresee marketing in England).",keyPrinciple:"The Art 5 cascade moves through habitual residence → acquisition → damage, stopping at the first country where the product was marketed."},
  {id:37,number:"Rome II – Art 6(1)",subtopic:"Unfair competition",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 6(1)",question:"What law governs non-contractual obligations arising from acts of unfair competition under Rome II?",answer:"Art 6(1): the law of the country where competitive relations or the collective interests of consumers are, or are likely to be, affected.",keyPrinciple:"Art 6(1) uses the market-effects test for unfair competition — the law of the affected market governs."},
  {id:38,number:"Rome II – Art 6(2)",subtopic:"Unfair competition",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 6(2)",question:"When is a competitor-specific unfair competition claim removed from the general unfair competition choice of law rule, and what applies instead?",answer:"Art 6(2): where an act of unfair competition affects exclusively the interests of a specific competitor (rather than the market or consumers generally), Art 4 applies — the general tort rule.",keyPrinciple:"Art 6(1) protects the market; where only a single competitor is targeted, the general Art 4 rule applies instead."},
  {id:39,number:"Rome II – Art 6(3)",subtopic:"Restriction of competition",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 6(3)",question:"What law governs non-contractual obligations arising from a restriction of competition under Rome II, and what option is available where multiple markets are affected?",answer:"Art 6(3)(a): the law of the country where the market is, or is likely to be, affected. Art 6(3)(b): where multiple markets are affected and the claimant sues in a UK court, the claimant may instead choose to base the claim on the law of the court seised, provided the UK market is amongst those directly and substantially affected.",keyPrinciple:"Art 6(3) uses the affected-market test; a lex fori option is available in multi-market cases where the forum market is substantially affected."},
  {id:40,number:"Rome II – Art 6(4)",subtopic:"Restriction of competition",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 6(4)",question:"Can parties derogate from the law applicable to competition-related non-contractual obligations under Rome II by agreement?",answer:"No. Art 6(4) expressly provides that the law applicable under Art 6 may not be derogated from by an agreement under Art 14. Competition law obligations are mandatory.",keyPrinciple:"Art 6 is party-autonomy proof — parties cannot contract out of the applicable competition law by a choice of law agreement."},
  {id:41,number:"Rome II – Art 7",subtopic:"Environmental damage",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 7",question:"What is the choice of law rule for environmental damage under Rome II, and what special option does it give the claimant?",answer:"Art 7: the law applicable is determined pursuant to Art 4(1) — lex loci damni. However, the person seeking compensation may choose instead to base the claim on the law of the country in which the event giving rise to the damage occurred (lex loci actus).",keyPrinciple:"Art 7 gives the environmental damage claimant a unilateral choice between lex loci damni and lex loci actus — reflecting the polluter-pays principle."},
  {id:42,number:"Rome II – Art 8",subtopic:"IP infringement",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 8",question:"What law governs non-contractual obligations arising from intellectual property infringement under Rome II, and can parties derogate from it?",answer:"Art 8(1): the law of the country for which protection is claimed (lex loci protectionis). Art 8(3): the law applicable under Art 8 may not be derogated from by an agreement under Art 14.",keyPrinciple:"IP infringement is governed by lex loci protectionis and is mandatory — party autonomy is excluded."},
  {id:43,number:"Rome II – Art 9",subtopic:"Industrial action",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 9",question:"What law governs liability for industrial action under Rome II?",answer:"Art 9: without prejudice to Art 4(2), the law of the country where the action is to be, or has been, taken governs liability for industrial action — whether the defendant is a worker, employer, or representative organisation.",keyPrinciple:"Art 9 applies the law of the place of industrial action, reflecting the territorial nature of labour relations."},
  {id:44,number:"Rome II – Art 10",subtopic:"Unjust enrichment",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 10",question:"Describe the four-step hierarchy for determining the applicable law for unjust enrichment under Rome II.",answer:"Art 10: (1) if the unjust enrichment concerns a pre-existing relationship between the parties (contract or tort), the law governing that relationship applies; (2) failing that, if parties share habitual residence, that law applies; (3) failing that, the law of the country where the unjust enrichment took place; (4) if manifestly more closely connected with another country, that country's law applies.",keyPrinciple:"Art 10 anchors unjust enrichment to any pre-existing relationship first, then falls back through habitual residence and place of enrichment."},
  {id:45,number:"Rome II – Art 10 scenario",subtopic:"Unjust enrichment",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 10",question:"A (English) mistakenly overpays B (French) under a contract governed by German law. Which law governs the unjust enrichment claim?",answer:"Art 10(1) applies — the unjust enrichment concerns a pre-existing contractual relationship. German law (the law governing the contract) applies to the unjust enrichment claim.",keyPrinciple:"Where unjust enrichment arises from a pre-existing contract, the law governing the contract governs the enrichment claim."},
  {id:46,number:"Rome II – Art 11",subtopic:"Negotiorum gestio",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 11",question:"Describe the hierarchy for determining the applicable law for negotiorum gestio (unauthorised management of another's affairs) under Rome II.",answer:"Art 11: (1) if the obligation concerns a pre-existing relationship, the law governing that relationship applies; (2) failing that, the law of the country of common habitual residence; (3) failing that, the law of the country where the act was performed; (4) escape clause — manifestly more closely connected country.",keyPrinciple:"Art 11 mirrors Art 10 in structure — pre-existing relationship first, then habitual residence, then place of act, then escape clause."},
  {id:47,number:"Rome II – Art 12",subtopic:"Culpa in contrahendo",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 12",question:"What law governs non-contractual obligations arising from pre-contractual dealings under Rome II?",answer:"Art 12(1): the law that applies (or would have applied) to the contract. Art 12(2): where that cannot be determined — (a) lex loci damni; (b) common habitual residence; (c) manifestly more closely connected country.",keyPrinciple:"Art 12 anchors culpa in contrahendo to the (actual or putative) contract law — keeping pre-contractual and contractual obligations under the same governing law."},
  {id:48,number:"Rome II – Art 12 scenario",subtopic:"Culpa in contrahendo",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 12",question:"During negotiations for a contract, A (English company) fails to disclose a material fact to B (French company), causing B loss. No contract is ever concluded. What law governs B's claim under Rome II?",answer:"Art 12(1) applies — the law that would have applied to the contract had it been entered into. The court must determine what law would have governed the putative contract (e.g. under Rome I rules), and that law governs the culpa in contrahendo claim.",keyPrinciple:"Art 12 applies even where no contract was concluded — the governing law is what would have applied to the putative contract."},
  {id:49,number:"Rome II – Art 13",subtopic:"IP and non-tort obligations",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 13",question:"What does Rome II provide regarding intellectual property rights in the context of unjust enrichment, negotiorum gestio and culpa in contrahendo?",answer:"Art 13: for non-contractual obligations arising from IP infringement within Chapter III (Arts 10-12), Art 8 (lex loci protectionis) applies. IP claims do not follow the usual culpa in contrahendo or unjust enrichment rules.",keyPrinciple:"Art 13 preserves the primacy of lex loci protectionis for IP obligations even where they arise in a pre-contractual or enrichment context."},
  {id:50,number:"Rome II – Art 14",subtopic:"Party autonomy",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 14",question:"Can parties choose the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation under Rome II? If so, when and subject to what constraints?",answer:"Art 14(1): parties may choose the applicable law (a) by agreement after the event giving rise to damage; or (b) where all parties are pursuing commercial activity, by a freely negotiated agreement before the event. Choice must be expressed or clearly demonstrated. Art 14(2): where all elements are located in one country, choice cannot override that country's mandatory rules. Art 14(3): same protection for intra-UK situations.",keyPrinciple:"Party autonomy in Rome II is permitted but limited — pre-event choice is commercial-only, and mandatory rules of a purely domestic situation are preserved."},
  {id:51,number:"Rome II – Art 15",subtopic:"Scope of applicable law",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 15",question:"What matters does the applicable law govern under Rome II?",answer:"Art 15: the applicable law governs (a) basis and extent of liability; (b) grounds for exemption, limitation and division of liability; (c) existence, nature and assessment of damage or remedy; (d) preventive/protective measures within the court's procedural powers; (e) transferability of claims including by inheritance; (f) persons entitled to compensation personally; (g) liability for acts of another; (h) prescription and limitation, including commencement, interruption and suspension.",keyPrinciple:"Art 15 gives the applicable law broad scope — it governs substantive liability, remedies, limitation periods and third-party liability, but not procedure."},
  {id:52,number:"Rome II – Art 16",subtopic:"Overriding mandatory provisions",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 16",question:"What does Rome II provide regarding overriding mandatory provisions of the forum?",answer:"Art 16: nothing in Rome II restricts the application of provisions of the law of the forum which are mandatory irrespective of the law otherwise applicable to the non-contractual obligation.",keyPrinciple:"Art 16 preserves the forum's overriding mandatory provisions — they apply regardless of the law designated by Rome II."},
  {id:53,number:"Rome II – Art 17",subtopic:"Rules of safety and conduct",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 17",question:"What does Rome II require courts to take into account when assessing the conduct of the person claimed to be liable?",answer:"Art 17: in assessing the conduct of the person claimed to be liable, account shall be taken, as a matter of fact and in so far as appropriate, of the rules of safety and conduct which were in force at the place and time of the event giving rise to liability.",keyPrinciple:"Art 17 requires factual account of local safety rules at the place of the act — even where a different law governs the substance of liability."},
  {id:54,number:"Rome II – Art 17 scenario",subtopic:"Rules of safety and conduct",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 17",question:"A road accident occurs in France. The common habitual residence exception applies so English law governs the substance of liability. French road traffic regulations impose a lower speed limit than English law. Must the court take French speed limits into account?",answer:"Yes. Art 17 requires the court to take into account, as a matter of fact, the rules of safety and conduct in force at the place and time of the event — here French road traffic rules. This applies even though English law governs the substance of liability.",keyPrinciple:"Art 17 operates independently of the governing law — local safety rules at the place of the act are always factually relevant to the assessment of conduct."},
  {id:55,number:"Rome II – Art 18",subtopic:"Direct action against insurer",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 18",question:"Under what circumstances can a victim bring a direct claim against the defendant's insurer under Rome II?",answer:"Art 18: the person who suffered damage may bring a claim directly against the insurer of the person liable if the law applicable to the non-contractual obligation or the law applicable to the insurance contract so provides.",keyPrinciple:"Art 18 permits direct action against an insurer if either the tort's applicable law or the insurance contract's applicable law allows it."},
  {id:56,number:"Rome II – Art 21",subtopic:"Formal validity",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 21",question:"What law governs the formal validity of a unilateral act relating to a non-contractual obligation under Rome II?",answer:"Art 21: a unilateral act intended to have legal effect relating to a non-contractual obligation is formally valid if it satisfies the formal requirements of either (a) the law governing the non-contractual obligation, or (b) the law of the country in which the act is performed.",keyPrinciple:"Art 21 offers alternative reference for formal validity — either the governing law or the law of the place of the act."},
  {id:57,number:"Rome II – Art 22",subtopic:"Burden of proof",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 22",question:"What does Rome II provide regarding burden of proof and modes of proof?",answer:"Art 22(1): the applicable law governs rules which raise presumptions of law or determine the burden of proof. Art 22(2): acts intended to have legal effect may be proved by any mode of proof recognised by the lex fori or by any law under which the act is formally valid, provided that mode can be administered by the forum.",keyPrinciple:"Burden of proof is governed by the applicable law; mode of proof is flexible — either lex fori or the law under which the act is formally valid."},
  {id:58,number:"Rome II – Art 23",subtopic:"Habitual residence",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 23",question:"How does Rome II define habitual residence for companies and for individuals acting in the course of business?",answer:"Art 23(1): for companies and other bodies, habitual residence is the place of central administration. Where damage arises in the course of operation of a branch/agency/establishment, that location is treated as the habitual residence. Art 23(2): for a natural person acting in the course of business, habitual residence is the principal place of business.",keyPrinciple:"Art 23 uses central administration for companies and principal place of business for individuals in business — with a branch/agency exception for operational damage."},
  {id:59,number:"Rome II – Art 24",subtopic:"Renvoi",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 24",question:"Which Rome II provision excludes renvoi, and what does it provide?",answer:"Art 24: the application of the law of any country specified by Rome II means the application of the rules of law in force in that country other than its rules of private international law. Renvoi is excluded.",keyPrinciple:"Rome II designates the domestic law of a country only — its conflict of laws rules are never applied."},
  {id:60,number:"Rome II – Art 25",subtopic:"Multi-law states",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 25",question:"How does Rome II treat states with more than one legal system, such as the US or Australia?",answer:"Art 25(1): where a state comprises several territorial units each with its own rules for non-contractual obligations, each territorial unit is treated as a country for the purposes of identifying the applicable law.",keyPrinciple:"In multi-law states, each territorial unit is treated as a separate 'country' for Rome II choice of law purposes."},
  {id:61,number:"Rome II – Art 26",subtopic:"Public policy",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 26",question:"Which Rome II provision contains the public policy exception, and what is the threshold for its application?",answer:"Art 26: the application of a provision of any law specified by Rome II may be refused only if such application is manifestly incompatible with the public policy (ordre public) of the forum. The threshold is high — mere difference or undesirability is insufficient.",keyPrinciple:"Art 26 is a narrow safety valve — 'manifestly incompatible' sets a high bar; the exception cannot be used simply because foreign law differs from forum law."},
  {id:62,number:"Rome II – Art 26 scenario",subtopic:"Public policy",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome II, Art 26",question:"The applicable law under Rome II awards punitive damages three times the compensatory sum. Can an English court refuse to apply this on public policy grounds?",answer:"Possibly — Art 26 permits refusal where application would be manifestly incompatible with forum public policy. Recital 32 specifically contemplates that excessive non-compensatory punitive damages may engage public policy. However, the threshold is high and the court should consider whether the damages are genuinely excessive rather than merely unfamiliar.",keyPrinciple:"Excessive punitive damages are the paradigm Rome II public policy case — but 'manifestly incompatible' is a high threshold, not a general anti-foreign law discretion."},
  {id:63,number:"Rome II – Art 28/31",subtopic:"Application in time",tags:["topic:Choice - Tort","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome II, Art 28/31",question:"From what date does Rome II apply in England and Wales, and what is the relevant trigger event?",answer:"Rome II applies to events giving rise to damage occurring on or after IP completion day (31 December 2020) for international conflicts. For intra-UK conflicts (including UK/Gibraltar), it applies to events on or after 11 January 2009. The trigger is the event giving rise to damage, not when proceedings are brought.",keyPrinciple:"Rome II applies to the event giving rise to damage — its temporal scope depends on when the harmful event occurred, not when the claim is brought."},
  {id:64,number:"Rome I – Art 1(2)",subtopic:"Scope",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 1(2)",question:"Name the categories of contractual obligation excluded from the scope of Rome I.",answer:"Art 1(2) excludes: (a) status and legal capacity of natural persons (without prejudice to Art 13); (b) family relationships and maintenance; (c) matrimonial property regimes and comparable relationships, wills and succession; (d) bills of exchange and negotiable instruments; (e) arbitration agreements and choice of court agreements; (f) company law matters (creation, capacity, internal organisation, winding-up, officers' and members' personal liability); (g) agency — whether an agent can bind a principal; (h) trusts (constitution and settlor/trustee/beneficiary relationships); (i) pre-contractual obligations; (j) certain insurance contracts for non-EU/UK undertakings.",keyPrinciple:"Rome I mirrors Rome II in excluding family, company and trust matters — but uniquely also excludes arbitration/choice of court agreements and pre-contractual obligations (which fall under Rome II Art 12)."},
  {id:65,number:"Rome I – Art 2",subtopic:"Universal application",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 2",question:"Must an English court apply the law designated by Rome I even if it is not the law of a Rome I state?",answer:"Yes. Art 2 provides for universal application — the law specified by Rome I shall be applied whether or not it is the law of the UK or a Member State. Rome I can therefore designate the law of any country in the world.",keyPrinciple:"Like Rome II, Rome I operates universally — it can designate any country's law, not just EU/UK law."},
  {id:66,number:"Rome I – Art 3(1)",subtopic:"Freedom of choice",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 3(1); Recital 11",question:"What is the primary rule for determining the law applicable to a contract under Rome I, and how must the choice be made?",answer:"Art 3(1): a contract shall be governed by the law chosen by the parties. The choice shall be made expressly or be clearly demonstrated by the terms of the contract or the circumstances of the case. Parties may choose the law applicable to the whole or part only of the contract. As Recital 11 emphasises, freedom of choice is the cornerstone of the Rome I system.",keyPrinciple:"Party autonomy is the cornerstone of Rome I — express or clearly demonstrated choice governs, and partial choice of law is permitted."},
  {id:67,number:"Rome I – Art 3(2)",subtopic:"Freedom of choice",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 3(2)",question:"Can parties change the governing law after the contract has been concluded, and what are the limits on doing so?",answer:"Art 3(2): yes — the parties may at any time agree to subject the contract to a law other than that which previously governed it. However, any change made after conclusion shall not prejudice the formal validity of the contract under Art 11 or adversely affect the rights of third parties.",keyPrinciple:"Post-conclusion change of governing law is permitted but cannot retrospectively invalidate formal validity or prejudice third-party rights."},
  {id:68,number:"Rome I – Art 3(3)",subtopic:"Freedom of choice",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 3(3); Recital 15",question:"What limits does Rome I place on choice of law where all elements of the contract are located in a single country other than the chosen law's country?",answer:"Art 3(3): where all other elements relevant to the situation at the time of choice are located in a country other than the chosen law's country, the choice shall not prejudice the application of provisions of that other country which cannot be derogated from by agreement. Recital 15 confirms this is a purely domestic situation rule — the choice of law stands but cannot override mandatory rules of the country with which the contract is entirely connected.",keyPrinciple:"A purely domestic contract cannot escape its own country's mandatory rules by choosing foreign law — Art 3(3) preserves those rules despite the choice."},
  {id:69,number:"Rome I – Art 3(4)",subtopic:"Freedom of choice",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 3(4)",question:"What happens where parties to a contract choose a non-EU/UK law but all relevant elements are located in one or more relevant states?",answer:"Art 3(4): where all other elements relevant to the situation at the time of choice are located in one or more relevant states, the parties' choice of a non-relevant-state law shall not prejudice the application of assimilated EU law provisions which cannot be derogated from by agreement. This is the intra-EU/UK equivalent of Art 3(3).",keyPrinciple:"Art 3(4) mirrors Art 3(3) for intra-EU/UK situations — mandatory EU/UK law provisions cannot be avoided by choosing a third-country law."},
  {id:70,number:"Rome I – Art 3 scenario",subtopic:"Freedom of choice",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome I, Art 3(1) and Art 3(3)",question:"A and B, both domiciled and operating in France, enter into a commercial contract with no international elements. They include a clause choosing English law. A sues B in France for breach. Does English law govern?",answer:"Art 3(1) gives effect to the choice of English law. However, under Art 3(3), the choice cannot displace French mandatory rules since all elements of the situation are located in France. English law governs the contract generally, but French provisions that cannot be derogated from by agreement continue to apply.",keyPrinciple:"A choice of foreign law in a purely domestic contract is effective but cannot displace the mandatory rules of the country where all elements are located."},
  {id:71,number:"Rome I – Art 4 (overview)",subtopic:"Applicable law in absence of choice",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4; Recitals 16, 19–21",question:"Describe the overall structure of Rome I's rules for determining the applicable law where parties have made no choice.",answer:"Art 4 operates in four tiers: (1) specific rules for eight contract types under Art 4(1)(a)-(h); (2) the characteristic performance rule under Art 4(2) for contracts not covered or covered by more than one type; (3) the escape clause under Art 4(3) where the contract is manifestly more closely connected with another country; (4) the closest connection fallback under Art 4(4) where the law cannot be determined under (1) or (2). Recital 16 emphasises foreseeability; Recital 19 explains characteristic performance; Recital 20 addresses the escape clause.",keyPrinciple:"Art 4 is a hierarchy: specific type rules first, then characteristic performance, then escape clause, then closest connection as a last resort."},
  {id:72,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(a)",subtopic:"Sale of goods",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(a)",question:"In the absence of choice, what law governs a contract for the sale of goods under Rome I?",answer:"Art 4(1)(a): the law of the country where the seller has his habitual residence.",keyPrinciple:"Sale of goods — seller's habitual residence."},
  {id:73,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(b)",subtopic:"Provision of services",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(b); Recital 17",question:"In the absence of choice, what law governs a contract for the provision of services under Rome I?",answer:"Art 4(1)(b): the law of the country where the service provider has his habitual residence. Recital 17 notes that 'provision of services' should be interpreted consistently with Brussels I Regulation Art 5.",keyPrinciple:"Provision of services — service provider's habitual residence."},
  {id:74,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(c)",subtopic:"Immovable property",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(c)",question:"In the absence of choice, what law governs a contract relating to a right in rem in immovable property or a tenancy of immovable property under Rome I?",answer:"Art 4(1)(c): the law of the country where the property is situated (lex situs).",keyPrinciple:"Immovable property contracts — lex situs."},
  {id:75,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(d)",subtopic:"Short-term tenancy",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(d)",question:"When does the short-term tenancy exception apply under Rome I, and what law governs instead of lex situs?",answer:"Art 4(1)(d): notwithstanding Art 4(1)(c), a tenancy concluded for temporary private use for no more than six consecutive months is governed by the law of the country where the landlord has his habitual residence — provided the tenant is a natural person and has his habitual residence in the same country as the landlord.",keyPrinciple:"Short-term holiday lets (≤6 months, same-country landlord and tenant) are governed by the landlord's habitual residence, not lex situs."},
  {id:76,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(e)",subtopic:"Franchise contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(e)",question:"In the absence of choice, what law governs a franchise contract under Rome I?",answer:"Art 4(1)(e): the law of the country where the franchisee has his habitual residence.",keyPrinciple:"Franchise contracts — franchisee's habitual residence (reflecting the weaker party in need of protection)."},
  {id:77,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(f)",subtopic:"Distribution contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(f)",question:"In the absence of choice, what law governs a distribution contract under Rome I?",answer:"Art 4(1)(f): the law of the country where the distributor has his habitual residence.",keyPrinciple:"Distribution contracts — distributor's habitual residence."},
  {id:78,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(g)",subtopic:"Sale by auction",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(g)",question:"In the absence of choice, what law governs a contract for the sale of goods by auction under Rome I?",answer:"Art 4(1)(g): the law of the country where the auction takes place, if such a place can be determined.",keyPrinciple:"Sale by auction — law of the place of the auction, if determinable."},
  {id:79,number:"Rome I – Art 4(1)(h)",subtopic:"Multilateral systems",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(1)(h); Recital 18",question:"In the absence of choice, what law governs a contract concluded within a multilateral financial trading system under Rome I?",answer:"Art 4(1)(h): a contract concluded within a multilateral system which brings together multiple third-party buying and selling interests in financial instruments, in accordance with non-discretionary rules and governed by a single law, shall be governed by that single law. Recital 18 identifies regulated markets and multilateral trading facilities as examples.",keyPrinciple:"Contracts on regulated financial markets — the single law governing the multilateral system applies, ensuring uniformity of terms."},
  {id:80,number:"Rome I – Art 4(2)",subtopic:"Characteristic performance",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(2); Recital 19",question:"What is the characteristic performance rule under Rome I, and when does it apply?",answer:"Art 4(2): where the contract is not covered by Art 4(1) or where its elements fall within more than one of Art 4(1)(a)-(h), it shall be governed by the law of the country where the party required to effect the characteristic performance has his habitual residence. Recital 19 explains that characteristic performance is the performance for which payment is due — i.e. the non-monetary obligation — and that for mixed contracts the centre of gravity determines it.",keyPrinciple:"Characteristic performance is the non-monetary performance — the law of the habitual residence of the party who performs it governs absent a specific Art 4(1) rule."},
  {id:81,number:"Rome I – Art 4(2) scenario",subtopic:"Characteristic performance",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(2); Recital 19",question:"A German company agrees to design and install bespoke software for an English company. No governing law is chosen. The contract does not fall within any specific Art 4(1) category. Which law governs?",answer:"Art 4(2) applies. The characteristic performance is the design and installation of the software — the non-monetary obligation performed by the German company. The law of Germany (the German company's habitual residence) governs.",keyPrinciple:"Where no specific Art 4(1) rule applies, identify the party performing the non-monetary obligation — their habitual residence law governs under Art 4(2)."},
  {id:82,number:"Rome I – Art 4(3)",subtopic:"Escape clause",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(3); Recital 20",question:"What is the escape clause under Rome I for contracts where no law has been chosen, and when does it apply?",answer:"Art 4(3): where it is clear from all the circumstances of the case that the contract is manifestly more closely connected with a country other than that indicated in Arts 4(1) or 4(2), the law of that other country shall apply. Recital 20 notes that a very close relationship with another contract may be relevant in determining the more closely connected country.",keyPrinciple:"Art 4(3) is a high-threshold escape clause — 'manifestly more closely connected' requires clear and compelling circumstances, not merely a balance of factors."},
  {id:83,number:"Rome I – Art 4(3) scenario",subtopic:"Escape clause",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(3); Recital 20",question:"A Spanish subcontractor agrees to carry out work in Spain under a subcontract with a French main contractor. The main contract between the French contractor and the employer is governed by French law. No law is chosen for the subcontract. The characteristic performance rule points to Spanish law. Can the escape clause apply?",answer:"Possibly. Under Art 4(3), if it is clear from all circumstances that the subcontract is manifestly more closely connected with France — e.g. it is directly linked to and must be read alongside the French-law main contract — French law may apply. Recital 20 specifically identifies close connection with another contract as a relevant factor.",keyPrinciple:"A subcontract closely tied to a main contract governed by a different law is the paradigm case for the Art 4(3) escape clause."},
  {id:84,number:"Rome I – Art 4(4)",subtopic:"Closest connection fallback",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 4(4); Recital 21",question:"When does the closest connection fallback under Rome I apply, and what does it provide?",answer:"Art 4(4): where the applicable law cannot be determined under Art 4(1) or Art 4(2), the contract shall be governed by the law of the country with which it is most closely connected. Recital 21 confirms this is a last resort, and that very close relationship with another contract may be taken into account.",keyPrinciple:"Art 4(4) is the final fallback — closest connection applies only where neither specific rules nor characteristic performance can determine the governing law."},
  {id:85,number:"Rome I – Art 5(1)",subtopic:"Carriage of goods",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 5(1); Recital 22",question:"What law governs a contract for the carriage of goods under Rome I in the absence of choice, and what is the primary connecting factor?",answer:"Art 5(1): the law of the country of habitual residence of the carrier, provided that the place of receipt, the place of delivery, or the habitual residence of the consignor is also situated in that country. If those requirements are not met, the law of the agreed place of delivery applies. Recital 22 confirms single-voyage charter parties are treated as contracts for the carriage of goods.",keyPrinciple:"Carriage of goods — carrier's habitual residence governs if it coincides with receipt, delivery or consignor's residence; otherwise the agreed place of delivery."},
  {id:86,number:"Rome I – Art 5(2)",subtopic:"Carriage of passengers",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 5(2)",question:"What law governs a contract for the carriage of passengers under Rome I, and what restricted choice of law is available to the parties?",answer:"Art 5(2): in the absence of choice, the law of the passenger's habitual residence governs, provided either the place of departure or the place of destination is in that country; otherwise the carrier's habitual residence governs. The parties may choose only from: (a) passenger's habitual residence; (b) carrier's habitual residence; (c) carrier's place of central administration; (d) place of departure; (e) place of destination.",keyPrinciple:"Carriage of passengers — restricted party autonomy; only five laws may be chosen, reflecting passenger protection."},
  {id:87,number:"Rome I – Art 6(1)",subtopic:"Consumer contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 6(1); Recitals 24–25",question:"What law governs a consumer contract under Rome I in the absence of choice, and what must the professional have done to trigger this rule?",answer:"Art 6(1): a contract concluded by a consumer with a professional shall be governed by the law of the country where the consumer has his habitual residence, provided the professional (a) pursues commercial or professional activities in that country, or (b) by any means directs such activities to that country or to several countries including that country, and the contract falls within the scope of those activities. Recitals 24–25 confirm the directed activity test is borrowed from Brussels I and requires more than mere internet accessibility.",keyPrinciple:"Consumer contracts are governed by the law of the consumer's habitual residence — but only where the professional directed activities to that country."},
  {id:88,number:"Rome I – Art 6(2)",subtopic:"Consumer contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 6(2); Recital 25",question:"Can parties choose the governing law in a consumer contract under Rome I, and what protection does the consumer retain?",answer:"Art 6(2): yes — the parties may choose the applicable law pursuant to Art 3. However, such a choice may not deprive the consumer of the protection afforded by provisions that cannot be derogated from by agreement under the law of the consumer's habitual residence (the Art 6(1) law). Recital 25 confirms the consumer retains the benefit of their home country's mandatory consumer protections regardless of choice.",keyPrinciple:"Choice of law is permitted in consumer contracts but cannot strip the consumer of mandatory protections under the law of their habitual residence."},
  {id:89,number:"Rome I – Art 6(4)",subtopic:"Consumer contracts — exclusions",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 6(4)",question:"Name the contracts excluded from the Rome I consumer protection rule.",answer:"Art 6(4) excludes: (a) contracts for services supplied exclusively in a country other than the consumer's habitual residence; (b) contracts of carriage other than package travel; (c) contracts relating to rights in rem in immovable property or tenancies (other than timeshare); (d) financial instruments and transferable securities; (e) contracts within multilateral systems under Art 4(1)(h).",keyPrinciple:"The consumer protection rule does not apply to transport, standard financial instruments, most property contracts, or services supplied entirely abroad."},
  {id:90,number:"Rome I – Art 6 scenario",subtopic:"Consumer contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome I, Art 6(1)–(2); Recital 25",question:"An Australian company operates a website in English with a prominent 'UK customers welcome' banner. A UK consumer purchases goods and the contract contains a clause choosing Australian law. A dispute arises. Which law governs?",answer:"Art 6(1) is triggered — the Australian company directed its activities to the UK by the banner and UK-targeted marketing. In the absence of choice, UK law would govern. The choice of Australian law under Art 6(2) is effective but cannot deprive the UK consumer of mandatory protections under UK consumer law. The consumer retains those protections regardless of the choice of Australian law.",keyPrinciple:"Directed activity to the consumer's country triggers Art 6 — a professional choice of foreign law stands but cannot undercut the consumer's mandatory home-law protections."},
  {id:91,number:"Rome I – Art 7 (large risk)",subtopic:"Insurance — large risk",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 7(2)",question:"What law governs an insurance contract covering a large risk under Rome I, and what happens in the absence of choice?",answer:"Art 7(2): an insurance contract covering a large risk (as defined in the Solvency II Directive) shall be governed by the law chosen by the parties under Art 3. In the absence of choice, it is governed by the law of the country where the insurer has his habitual residence, with an escape clause for manifestly closer connection.",keyPrinciple:"Large risk insurance enjoys full party autonomy under Art 3 — absence of choice points to the insurer's habitual residence."},
  {id:92,number:"Rome I – Art 7 (non-large risk)",subtopic:"Insurance — non-large risk",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 7(3)",question:"What restricted choice of law applies to non-large risk insurance contracts under Rome I?",answer:"Art 7(3): for non-large risk insurance, parties may choose only from: (a) law of the relevant state where the risk is situated; (b) law of the policyholder's habitual residence; (c) for life assurance, law of the relevant state of the policyholder's nationality; (d) for risks limited to events in one relevant state, that state's law; (e) for commercial policyholders with risks in multiple relevant states, law of any of those states or the policyholder's habitual residence. Absent choice, the law of the relevant state where the risk is situated governs.",keyPrinciple:"Non-large risk insurance has restricted party autonomy — only a closed list of laws may be chosen, and absent choice the lex loci risci governs."},
  {id:93,number:"Rome I – Art 8(1)",subtopic:"Employment contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 8(1); Recital 35",question:"Can parties choose the governing law in an individual employment contract under Rome I, and what protection does the employee retain?",answer:"Art 8(1): yes — the parties may choose the applicable law under Art 3. However, such a choice may not deprive the employee of the protection afforded by provisions that cannot be derogated from by agreement under the law that would apply in the absence of choice (Arts 8(2)-(4)). Recital 35 confirms employees must not be deprived of protections from provisions that cannot be derogated from.",keyPrinciple:"Choice of law in employment is permitted but floored by the mandatory protections of the objectively applicable law — the employee always retains the benefit of the higher protection."},
  {id:94,number:"Rome I – Art 8(2)",subtopic:"Employment contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 8(2); Recital 36",question:"What is the primary connecting factor for employment contracts under Rome I in the absence of choice?",answer:"Art 8(2): the contract is governed by the law of the country in which, or failing that from which, the employee habitually carries out his work in performance of the contract. The country of habitual work shall not be deemed to have changed if the employee is temporarily employed in another country. Recital 36 confirms that a return to the country of origin after a temporary posting is expected.",keyPrinciple:"Employment contracts — law of the country of habitual work; temporary postings abroad do not change the habitual workplace."},
  {id:95,number:"Rome I – Art 8(3)",subtopic:"Employment contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 8(3)",question:"What law governs an employment contract where the employee does not habitually carry out work in any one country under Rome I?",answer:"Art 8(3): where the law applicable cannot be determined pursuant to Art 8(2), the contract shall be governed by the law of the country where the place of business through which the employee was engaged is situated.",keyPrinciple:"Where no single country of habitual work exists, the law of the place of the engaging business establishment governs."},
  {id:96,number:"Rome I – Art 8(4)",subtopic:"Employment contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 8(4)",question:"What is the escape clause for employment contracts under Rome I?",answer:"Art 8(4): where it appears from the circumstances as a whole that the contract is more closely connected with a country other than that indicated in Arts 8(2) or 8(3), the law of that other country shall apply. Note: unlike Art 4(3), there is no 'manifestly' threshold — a closer connection suffices.",keyPrinciple:"The employment escape clause has a lower threshold than Art 4(3) — a closer connection (not 'manifestly' closer) is sufficient to displace the primary rules."},
  {id:97,number:"Rome I – Art 8 scenario",subtopic:"Employment contracts",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome I, Art 8(1)–(2); Recital 35",question:"A French employee is recruited by a UK company in London and sent to work in Germany for three years, after which she is expected to return to London. Her contract chooses English law and contains fewer protections than German mandatory employment law. A dispute arises during the German posting. Which law governs?",answer:"Art 8(2): Germany is the country of habitual work during the posting. However, Recital 36 indicates that a temporary posting does not change the habitual workplace if return is expected — so London remains the habitual workplace and English law governs under Art 8(2). Under Art 8(1), the choice of English law is effective but cannot deprive the employee of German mandatory protections applicable during the German posting (arguably via Art 9(3) overriding mandatory provisions).",keyPrinciple:"A temporary posting does not shift the habitual workplace — but mandatory employment protections of the host country may still apply as overriding mandatory provisions under Art 9(3)."},
  {id:98,number:"Rome I – Art 9(1)",subtopic:"Overriding mandatory provisions",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 9(1); Recital 37",question:"How does Rome I define overriding mandatory provisions, and how does this differ from ordinary non-derogable provisions?",answer:"Art 9(1): overriding mandatory provisions are provisions the respect for which is regarded as crucial by a country for safeguarding its public interests — such as its political, social or economic organisation — to such an extent that they apply to any situation within their scope irrespective of the applicable law. Recital 37 draws a sharp distinction: these are more restrictive than ordinary non-derogable provisions under Arts 6 and 8, which merely protect weaker parties.",keyPrinciple:"Overriding mandatory provisions (lois de police) are a narrow category — only provisions safeguarding fundamental public interests qualify, not merely protective consumer or employment rules."},
  {id:99,number:"Rome I – Art 9(2)",subtopic:"Overriding mandatory provisions",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 9(2)",question:"What does Rome I provide regarding overriding mandatory provisions of the forum?",answer:"Art 9(2): nothing in Rome I shall restrict the application of the overriding mandatory provisions of the law of the forum.",keyPrinciple:"Forum overriding mandatory provisions always apply — Rome I cannot displace them regardless of the governing law."},
  {id:100,number:"Rome I – Art 9(3)",subtopic:"Overriding mandatory provisions",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 9(3)",question:"In what circumstances may a court give effect to the overriding mandatory provisions of a third country under Rome I?",answer:"Art 9(3): effect may be given to the overriding mandatory provisions of the law of the country where the obligations arising out of the contract have to be or have been performed, in so far as those provisions render the performance of the contract unlawful. In considering whether to give effect to those provisions, regard shall be had to their nature and purpose and the consequences of their application or non-application.",keyPrinciple:"Third-country overriding mandatory provisions may be given effect only where they render performance unlawful at the place of performance — it is a discretion, not an obligation."},
  {id:101,number:"Rome I – Art 9(3) scenario",subtopic:"Overriding mandatory provisions",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Rome I, Art 9(3)",question:"An English company contracts to sell goods to a buyer in Country X, the contract being governed by English law. After the contract is concluded, Country X imposes an embargo making importation of the goods unlawful there. The seller refuses to perform. Can the buyer sue for breach?",answer:"Art 9(3) may apply: the mandatory embargo law of Country X (place of performance) renders performance unlawful there. An English court has discretion to give effect to the Country X embargo as an overriding mandatory provision. Regard must be had to its nature and purpose. If given effect, performance is excused and no breach arises — the seller is not liable.",keyPrinciple:"Art 9(3) gives courts discretion to excuse non-performance where third-country mandatory law makes performance unlawful at the place of performance."},
  {id:102,number:"Rome I – Art 10",subtopic:"Consent and material validity",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 10",question:"What law governs the existence and validity of a contract (or a term of a contract) under Rome I, and what exception exists for consent?",answer:"Art 10(1): the existence and validity of a contract or any term shall be determined by the law which would govern it under Rome I if the contract or term were valid (the putative applicable law). Art 10(2): however, a party may rely on the law of their habitual residence to establish that they did not consent, if it would not be reasonable to determine the effect of their conduct by the putative applicable law.",keyPrinciple:"Validity is governed by the putative applicable law — but a party may invoke their habitual residence law to deny consent where reliance on the putative law would be unreasonable."},
  {id:103,number:"Rome I – Art 11",subtopic:"Formal validity",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 11",question:"What laws may govern the formal validity of a contract under Rome I?",answer:"Art 11(1): a contract between parties in the same country is formally valid if it satisfies the formal requirements of either the substantive applicable law or the law of the country where it is concluded. Art 11(2): a contract between parties in different countries is formally valid if it satisfies the formal requirements of the substantive applicable law, or the law of either country where a party (or their agent) is present, or the law of either party's habitual residence. Art 11(5): immovable property contracts must also satisfy the mandatory formal requirements of the lex situs.",keyPrinciple:"Rome I is generous on formal validity — multiple alternative laws may validate a contract's form, with lex situs as an additional mandatory layer for immovable property."},
  {id:104,number:"Rome I – Art 12",subtopic:"Scope of applicable law",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 12",question:"What matters does the applicable law govern under Rome I?",answer:"Art 12(1): the applicable law governs (a) interpretation; (b) performance; (c) consequences of total or partial breach including damages assessment; (d) extinction of obligations and limitation; (e) consequences of nullity. Art 12(2): for the manner of performance and steps to be taken on defective performance, regard shall be had to the law of the country of performance.",keyPrinciple:"The applicable law governs interpretation, performance, breach, limitation and nullity — but manner of performance and defective performance remedies also look to the law of the place of performance."},
  {id:105,number:"Rome I – Art 13",subtopic:"Incapacity",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 13",question:"When may a party invoke incapacity under the law of another country in a contract concluded between persons in the same country under Rome I?",answer:"Art 13: in a contract between persons in the same country, a natural person who has capacity under that country's law may invoke incapacity under another country's law only if the other party knew of the incapacity at the time of conclusion, or did not know because of negligence.",keyPrinciple:"Art 13 protects good faith reliance on apparent capacity — a party cannot rely on foreign incapacity rules to escape a contract unless the other party knew or was negligent in not knowing."},
  {id:106,number:"Rome I – Art 14",subtopic:"Voluntary assignment",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 14; Recital 38",question:"What law governs the relationship between assignor and assignee, and what law governs the relationship between assignee and debtor, under Rome I?",answer:"Art 14(1): the relationship between assignor and assignee is governed by the law applicable to the contract between them under Rome I. Art 14(2): the law governing the assigned claim determines its assignability, the assignee-debtor relationship, the conditions for invoking the assignment against the debtor, and whether the debtor's obligations are discharged. Recital 38 clarifies that Art 14(1) covers proprietary aspects as between assignor and assignee where treated separately from obligations law.",keyPrinciple:"Assignor–assignee relations follow their contract's governing law; assignee–debtor relations and conditions of discharge follow the law of the assigned claim."},
  {id:107,number:"Rome I – Art 15",subtopic:"Legal subrogation",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 15",question:"What law determines whether and to what extent a third party who has satisfied a creditor is subrogated to the creditor's rights under Rome I?",answer:"Art 15: where a third person has a duty to satisfy the creditor, or has in fact satisfied the creditor in discharge of that duty, the law governing the third person's duty to satisfy the creditor determines whether and to what extent the third person may exercise against the debtor the rights which the creditor had against the debtor.",keyPrinciple:"Legal subrogation is governed by the law governing the third party's duty to pay — not the law of the underlying claim."},
  {id:108,number:"Rome I – Art 16",subtopic:"Multiple liability",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 16",question:"What law governs a co-debtor's right of recourse against other debtors after satisfying a common creditor under Rome I?",answer:"Art 16: if a creditor has a claim against several debtors liable for the same claim, and one debtor has already satisfied the claim in whole or in part, the law governing that debtor's obligation towards the creditor also governs the debtor's right to claim recourse from the other debtors. The other debtors may rely on defences they had against the creditor to the extent allowed by the law governing their obligations.",keyPrinciple:"Recourse between co-debtors is governed by the law governing the paying debtor's obligation to the creditor."},
  {id:109,number:"Rome I – Art 17",subtopic:"Set-off",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 17",question:"What law governs the right of set-off where the parties have not agreed on it under Rome I?",answer:"Art 17: where the right to set-off is not agreed by the parties, set-off shall be governed by the law applicable to the claim against which the right to set-off is asserted.",keyPrinciple:"Unilateral set-off is governed by the law of the claim against which it is asserted — not the law of the cross-claim."},
  {id:110,number:"Rome I – Art 18",subtopic:"Burden of proof",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 18",question:"What does Rome I provide regarding burden of proof and modes of proof in contractual matters?",answer:"Art 18(1): the applicable law under Rome I governs rules which raise presumptions of law or determine the burden of proof in contractual matters. Art 18(2): a contract or act may be proved by any mode of proof recognised by the lex fori or by any law under which the contract is formally valid (Art 11), provided that mode of proof can be administered by the forum.",keyPrinciple:"Burden of proof follows the applicable law; mode of proof is flexible — lex fori or any law validating the contract's form."},
  {id:111,number:"Rome I – Art 19",subtopic:"Habitual residence",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 19; Recital 39",question:"How does Rome I define habitual residence for companies, individuals acting in business, and where a branch is involved?",answer:"Art 19(1): for companies and other bodies, habitual residence is the place of central administration. For a natural person acting in the course of business, it is their principal place of business. Art 19(2): where the contract is concluded in the course of operations of a branch/agency/establishment, or performance is the responsibility of such a branch, that location is treated as the habitual residence. Art 19(3): the relevant point in time is the conclusion of the contract. Recital 39 emphasises a single criterion for companies to ensure foreseeability.",keyPrinciple:"Art 19 uses central administration for companies (not registered office) and principal place of business for individuals — assessed at the time of contracting, with a branch exception."},
  {id:112,number:"Rome I – Art 20",subtopic:"Renvoi",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 20",question:"Which Rome I provision excludes renvoi, and what does it provide?",answer:"Art 20: the application of the law of any country specified by Rome I means the application of the rules of law in force in that country other than its private international law rules, unless otherwise provided in Rome I.",keyPrinciple:"Rome I designates the domestic law of a country only — its conflict of laws rules are never applied."},
  {id:113,number:"Rome I – Art 21",subtopic:"Public policy",tags:["topic:Choice - Contracts","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Rome I, Art 21",question:"Which Rome I provision contains the public policy (ordre public) exception, and what is the threshold?",answer:"Art 21: the application of a provision of any law specified by Rome I may be refused only if such application is manifestly incompatible with the public policy (ordre public) of the forum.",keyPrinciple:"Art 21 mirrors Art 26 Rome II — 'manifestly incompatible' is a high threshold; routine difference from forum law does not suffice."},

  // --- HAGUE 2005 ---
  {id:114,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 1",subtopic:"Scope",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 1",question:"What is the scope of the Hague Convention on Choice of Court Agreements 2005?",answer:"Art 1: the Convention applies in international cases to exclusive choice of court agreements concluded in civil or commercial matters. A case is international for Chapter II purposes unless the parties are resident in the same Contracting State and all elements relevant to the dispute are connected only with that State. For Chapter III (recognition and enforcement), a case is international where recognition or enforcement of a foreign judgment is sought.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2005 applies to exclusive choice of court agreements in international civil and commercial matters — purely domestic cases fall outside Chapter II."},
  {id:115,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 2",subtopic:"Exclusions",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 2",question:"What categories of agreement and matter are excluded from the scope of Hague 2005?",answer:"Art 2(1) excludes agreements to which a consumer is a party, and agreements relating to individual contracts of employment. Art 2(2) excludes: (a) status and legal capacity of natural persons; (b) maintenance; (c) family law matters including matrimonial property; (d) wills and succession; (e) insolvency; (f) carriage of passengers and goods; (g) marine pollution, maritime claims limitation, general average, emergency towage and salvage; (h) anti-trust (competition); (i) nuclear damage liability; (j) personal injury claims by natural persons; (k) tort claims for tangible property damage not arising from a contractual relationship; (l) rights in rem and tenancies in immovable property; (m) validity of legal persons and their organs; (n) validity of IP rights other than copyright; (o) IP infringement other than contractual; (p) validity of public register entries. Art 2(4) excludes arbitration and related proceedings.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2005 excludes consumer and employment agreements, and a long list of subject-matter exclusions — notably competition, IP validity, personal injury, and arbitration."},
  {id:116,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 3",subtopic:"Exclusive choice of court agreements",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 3",question:"How does Hague 2005 define an exclusive choice of court agreement, and what is the deemed exclusivity rule?",answer:"Art 3(a): an exclusive choice of court agreement designates the courts of one Contracting State (or specific courts thereof) to the exclusion of any other courts, for disputes arising in connection with a particular legal relationship. Art 3(b): a choice of court agreement designating the courts of one Contracting State is deemed to be exclusive unless the parties have expressly provided otherwise. Art 3(c): the agreement must be concluded or documented in writing or by any other means rendering information accessible for subsequent reference. Art 3(d): the choice of court clause is treated as an independent agreement — its validity cannot be contested solely on the ground that the main contract is not valid (separability).",keyPrinciple:"Under Hague 2005, a choice of courts of one Contracting State is presumed exclusive; the agreement is separable from the main contract and its formal requirements are flexible."},
  {id:117,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 4",subtopic:"Definitions",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 4",question:"How does Hague 2005 define 'judgment', and how is residence of non-natural persons determined?",answer:"Art 4(1): 'judgment' means any decision on the merits by a court, whatever it may be called, including a decree or order, and a costs determination relating to a merits decision. Interim measures of protection are not judgments. Art 4(2): a non-natural person is resident in the State where it has its statutory seat, under whose law it was incorporated or formed, where it has its central administration, or where it has its principal place of business.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2005 excludes interim measures from the definition of judgment; corporate residence is determined by any one of four alternative connecting factors."},
  {id:118,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 5",subtopic:"Jurisdiction of chosen court",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 5",question:"What obligation does Hague 2005 impose on the chosen court, and can it decline jurisdiction on forum non conveniens grounds?",answer:"Art 5(1): the court or courts designated in an exclusive choice of court agreement shall have jurisdiction to decide the dispute, unless the agreement is null and void under the law of that State. Art 5(2): a court with jurisdiction under Art 5(1) shall not decline to exercise jurisdiction on the ground that the dispute should be decided in a court of another State. This abolishes forum non conveniens for Hague 2005 cases in the chosen court.",keyPrinciple:"The chosen court must hear the case and cannot decline on forum non conveniens grounds — Hague 2005 makes jurisdiction mandatory for the designated court."},
  {id:119,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 5 scenario",subtopic:"Jurisdiction of chosen court",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 5",question:"A commercial contract between an English and a French company contains an exclusive English jurisdiction clause. Both parties are in Contracting States. The French company commences proceedings in England. The English court considers staying proceedings in favour of France as a more convenient forum. Can it do so?",answer:"No. Under Art 5(1), the English court has jurisdiction as the designated court and under Art 5(2) it may not decline to exercise that jurisdiction on the ground that France would be a more convenient forum. Forum non conveniens is excluded by Hague 2005. The English court must hear the case.",keyPrinciple:"Art 5(2) abolishes forum non conveniens for the chosen court — once designated, it must hear the dispute regardless of convenience considerations."},
  {id:120,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 6",subtopic:"Obligations of non-chosen court",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 6",question:"What must a non-chosen court do when faced with proceedings covered by an exclusive choice of court agreement under Hague 2005, and what are the exceptions?",answer:"Art 6: a court of a Contracting State other than the chosen court must suspend or dismiss proceedings to which an exclusive choice of court agreement applies, unless: (a) the agreement is null and void under the law of the chosen court's State; (b) a party lacked capacity to conclude the agreement under the law of the court seised; (c) giving effect to the agreement would lead to manifest injustice or be manifestly contrary to the public policy of the State of the court seised; (d) for exceptional reasons beyond the parties' control, the agreement cannot reasonably be performed; or (e) the chosen court has decided not to hear the case.",keyPrinciple:"Non-chosen courts must suspend or dismiss — but five narrow exceptions permit retention of jurisdiction, including nullity, incapacity, manifest injustice and chosen court's refusal."},
  {id:121,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 6 scenario",subtopic:"Obligations of non-chosen court",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 6",question:"A contract designates French courts exclusively. One party sues in England. The defendant applies to stay the English proceedings. The claimant argues the clause was procured by fraud and is therefore void. What should the English court do?",answer:"The English court should consider whether the agreement is null and void under French law (the law of the chosen court's State) under Art 6(a). If null and void under French law, the English court may retain jurisdiction. However, the court seised is not bound by any finding of the French court on validity under Art 8(3) of Hague 2005. The English court should generally stay proceedings unless one of the Art 6 exceptions is clearly established.",keyPrinciple:"The non-chosen court assesses nullity under the law of the chosen court's State — it is not bound by that court's rulings on validity but should lean toward staying absent a clear exception."},
  {id:122,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 7",subtopic:"Interim measures",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 7",question:"Does Hague 2005 govern interim measures of protection?",answer:"Art 7: interim measures of protection are not governed by the Convention. The Convention neither requires nor precludes the grant, refusal or termination of interim measures by a court of a Contracting State, and does not affect whether a party may request or a court should grant, refuse or terminate such measures.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2005 is silent on interim measures — courts retain full discretion to grant or refuse them under their own law, regardless of the exclusive choice of court agreement."},
  {id:123,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 8",subtopic:"Recognition and enforcement",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 8",question:"What is the general obligation under Hague 2005 regarding recognition and enforcement of judgments from the chosen court, and what is the merits review rule?",answer:"Art 8(1): a judgment given by the chosen court shall be recognised and enforced in other Contracting States. Recognition or enforcement may be refused only on the grounds specified in the Convention. Art 8(2): there shall be no review of the merits of the judgment — the court addressed is bound by the findings of fact on which the court of origin based its jurisdiction, unless the judgment was given by default. Art 8(3): a judgment shall be recognised only if it has effect in the State of origin, and enforced only if it is enforceable there. Art 8(4): recognition or enforcement may be postponed or refused if the judgment is subject to review in the State of origin.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2005 mandates recognition and enforcement of judgments from the chosen court — no merits review is permitted, and the court addressed is bound by the original court's factual findings on jurisdiction."},
  {id:124,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 9",subtopic:"Grounds for refusal",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 9",question:"On what grounds may recognition or enforcement of a judgment be refused under Hague 2005?",answer:"Art 9: recognition or enforcement may be refused if: (a) the agreement was null and void under the law of the chosen court's State (unless the chosen court has determined it is valid); (b) a party lacked capacity to conclude the agreement under the law of the requested State; (c) the document instituting proceedings was not notified to the defendant in sufficient time to enable defence, unless the defendant appeared and presented the case without contesting notification; (d) the judgment was obtained by fraud in connection with procedure; (e) recognition or enforcement would be manifestly incompatible with the public policy of the requested State, including fundamental principles of procedural fairness; (f) the judgment is inconsistent with a judgment in the requested State between the same parties; (g) the judgment is inconsistent with an earlier judgment in another State between the same parties on the same cause of action, provided that earlier judgment fulfils conditions for recognition in the requested State.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2005 provides seven exhaustive grounds for refusal — they are narrow and largely mirror common law recognition defences: nullity, capacity, service, fraud, public policy, and inconsistent judgments."},
  {id:125,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 9 scenario",subtopic:"Grounds for refusal",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 9",question:"A French court (the chosen court) gives judgment against D. D seeks to resist enforcement in England, arguing: (i) the exclusive jurisdiction clause was null and void; and (ii) the French court had already determined the clause was valid. Can D rely on ground (a) of Art 9?",answer:"No. Art 9(a) provides that recognition or enforcement may be refused on the ground that the agreement was null and void under the law of the chosen court's State — but only unless the chosen court has determined that the agreement is valid. Since the French court (the chosen court) determined the clause valid, D cannot rely on Art 9(a). D would need to establish one of the other six grounds.",keyPrinciple:"Art 9(a) is unavailable where the chosen court has itself determined the agreement is valid — that finding forecloses the nullity ground in the requested State."},
  {id:126,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 10",subtopic:"Preliminary questions",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 10",question:"How does Hague 2005 treat rulings on excluded matters that arise as preliminary questions in proceedings?",answer:"Art 10(1): where an excluded matter arose as a preliminary question in the proceedings, the ruling on that question shall not be recognised or enforced under the Convention. Art 10(2): recognition or enforcement of a judgment may be refused if, and to the extent that, the judgment was based on a ruling on an excluded matter. Art 10(3): for IP validity (other than copyright), recognition or enforcement may be refused or postponed only where the ruling is inconsistent with a judgment or decision in the State under whose law the right arose, or where validity proceedings are pending there.",keyPrinciple:"Rulings on excluded preliminary questions are not enforceable under Hague 2005 — but the exclusion of the preliminary issue does not automatically exclude the whole judgment, only the part based on it."},
  {id:127,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 11",subtopic:"Damages",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 11",question:"What does Hague 2005 provide regarding recognition or enforcement of judgments awarding punitive or exemplary damages?",answer:"Art 11(1): recognition or enforcement of a judgment may be refused if, and to the extent that, the judgment awards damages — including exemplary or punitive damages — that do not compensate a party for actual loss or harm suffered. Art 11(2): the court addressed shall take into account whether and to what extent the damages awarded by the court of origin serve to cover costs and expenses relating to the proceedings.",keyPrinciple:"Non-compensatory punitive damages may be refused under Hague 2005 — but the court must consider whether part of the award covers costs before refusing enforcement of the whole sum."},
  {id:128,number:"Hague 2005 – Art 23",subtopic:"Uniform interpretation",tags:["topic:Choice of Court","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2005, Art 23",question:"What interpretive principle does Hague 2005 require courts to apply?",answer:"Art 23: in the interpretation of the Convention, regard shall be had to its international character and to the need to promote uniformity in its application.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2005 requires autonomous international interpretation — courts must look to the Convention's international character rather than domestic law concepts when construing its provisions."},

  // --- HAGUE 2019 ---
  {id:129,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 1",subtopic:"Scope",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 1",question:"What is the scope of the Hague Convention on the Recognition and Enforcement of Foreign Judgments 2019?",answer:"Art 1(1): the Convention applies to the recognition and enforcement of judgments in civil or commercial matters. It does not extend to revenue, customs or administrative matters. Art 1(2): the Convention applies to recognition and enforcement in one Contracting State of a judgment given by a court of another Contracting State.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2019 covers civil and commercial judgments between Contracting States — revenue, customs and administrative matters are excluded entirely."},
  {id:130,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 2",subtopic:"Exclusions",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 2",question:"What matters are excluded from the scope of Hague 2019, and what is notable about the competition exclusion?",answer:"Art 2(1) excludes: (a) status and legal capacity of natural persons; (b) maintenance; (c) family law and matrimonial property; (d) wills and succession; (e) insolvency and financial institution resolution; (f) carriage of passengers and goods; (g) transboundary and ship-source marine pollution, maritime claims limitation, general average; (h) nuclear damage; (i) validity, dissolution or decisions of organs of legal persons; (j) validity of public register entries; (k) defamation; (l) privacy; (m) intellectual property; (n) armed forces activities; (o) law enforcement activities; (p) anti-trust/competition — except where the judgment is based on a price-fixing, bid-rigging, output restriction or market allocation cartel where both the conduct and its effect occurred in the State of origin; (q) sovereign debt restructuring. Art 2(3) excludes arbitration and related proceedings.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2019 has a broader exclusion list than Hague 2005 — notably including defamation, privacy, IP, and law enforcement, but with a carve-in for hard-core cartel judgments where conduct and effect both occurred in the State of origin."},
  {id:131,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 3",subtopic:"Definitions",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 3",question:"How does Hague 2019 define 'judgment', and how is habitual residence of non-natural persons determined?",answer:"Art 3(1)(b): 'judgment' means any decision on the merits by a court, whatever it may be called, including a decree or order, and a costs determination relating to a merits decision. Interim measures of protection are not judgments. Art 3(2): a non-natural person is habitually resident in the State where it has its statutory seat, under whose law it was incorporated or formed, where it has its central administration, or where it has its principal place of business.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2019 mirrors Hague 2005 in excluding interim measures from the definition of judgment and in using four alternative connecting factors for corporate habitual residence."},
  {id:132,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 4",subtopic:"General provisions",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 4",question:"What is the general obligation of recognition and enforcement under Hague 2019, and what is the merits review rule?",answer:"Art 4(1): a judgment given by a court of a Contracting State shall be recognised and enforced in another Contracting State in accordance with the Convention. Recognition or enforcement may be refused only on the grounds specified. Art 4(2): there shall be no review of the merits of the judgment in the requested State — only such consideration as is necessary for the application of the Convention. Art 4(3): a judgment shall be recognised only if it has effect in the State of origin, and enforced only if it is enforceable there. Art 4(4): recognition or enforcement may be postponed or refused if the judgment is subject to review or if the time limit for ordinary review has not expired.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2019 prohibits merits review — the requested State must give effect to the judgment as given, subject only to the Convention's specific grounds for refusal."},
  {id:133,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 5",subtopic:"Bases for recognition and enforcement",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 5",question:"What are the bases upon which a judgment is eligible for recognition and enforcement under Hague 2019?",answer:"Art 5(1): a judgment is eligible if one of the following is met — (a) defendant habitually resident in State of origin when becoming a party; (b) natural person defendant had principal place of business in State of origin and claim arose out of those business activities; (c) defendant was the claimant in the original proceedings; (d) defendant maintained a branch/agency/establishment in the State of origin and the claim arose out of those activities; (e) defendant expressly consented to jurisdiction in the course of proceedings; (f) defendant argued on the merits without contesting jurisdiction within the prescribed time; (g) judgment ruled on a contractual obligation and was given by the court of the place of performance agreed by the parties or determined by the applicable law, unless the defendant's activities clearly had no purposeful and substantial connection to that State; (h) judgment ruled on a lease of immovable property and was given by the court of the State where the property is situated; (i) judgment ruled against the defendant on a contractual obligation secured by a right in rem in immovable property in the State of origin, where the contractual claim was brought together with a claim relating to that right in rem; (j) judgment ruled on a non-contractual obligation arising from death, physical injury, or damage to/loss of tangible property, and the act or omission directly causing harm occurred in the State of origin; (k) judgment concerns validity, construction, effects, administration or variation of a trust created voluntarily and evidenced in writing, where the State of origin was designated in the trust instrument as the forum or as the principal place of administration; (l) judgment ruled on a counterclaim — to the extent it was in favour of the counterclaimant where the counterclaim arose from the same transaction, or against the counterclaimant unless the law of the State of origin required the counterclaim to be filed to avoid preclusion; (m) judgment was given by a court designated in a written agreement (other than an exclusive choice of court agreement).",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2019 provides thirteen jurisdictional bases for recognition — they broadly track the connections that justify recognising a foreign judgment, from habitual residence and consent to place of performance and place of tort."},
  {id:134,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 5 scenario",subtopic:"Bases for recognition and enforcement",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 5",question:"A US court gives judgment against D, a company habitually resident in France, arising from a tort causing physical injury in the US. D argues the judgment should not be recognised in England under Hague 2019. Which basis for recognition applies?",answer:"Art 5(1)(j) applies: the judgment ruled on a non-contractual obligation arising from physical injury, and the act or omission directly causing the harm occurred in the State of origin (the US). This is a recognised basis for enforcement regardless of D's habitual residence in France. D's habitual residence in France does not prevent recognition — Art 5(1)(j) provides an independent basis.",keyPrinciple:"Art 5(1)(j) provides a basis for recognition of tort judgments where the direct harmful act or omission occurred in the State of origin — the defendant's residence elsewhere is irrelevant."},
  {id:135,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 6",subtopic:"Exclusive basis for immovable property",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 6",question:"What is the exclusive basis for recognition and enforcement of judgments ruling on rights in rem in immovable property under Hague 2019?",answer:"Art 6: notwithstanding Art 5, a judgment that ruled on rights in rem in immovable property shall be recognised and enforced if and only if the property is situated in the State of origin. No other basis in Art 5 can substitute for this requirement.",keyPrinciple:"Rights in rem in immovable property judgments are subject to an exclusive situs rule — only judgments from the State where the property is situated qualify for recognition under Hague 2019."},
  {id:136,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 7",subtopic:"Grounds for refusal",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 7",question:"On what grounds may recognition or enforcement of a judgment be refused under Hague 2019?",answer:"Art 7(1): recognition or enforcement may be refused if: (a) the document instituting proceedings was not notified to the defendant in sufficient time to enable defence (unless defendant appeared and presented the case without contesting notification), or was notified in the requested State in a manner incompatible with fundamental principles of service; (b) the judgment was obtained by fraud; (c) recognition or enforcement would be manifestly incompatible with the public policy of the requested State, including fundamental principles of procedural fairness and situations involving infringements of security or sovereignty; (d) the proceedings in the court of origin were contrary to an agreement or trust instrument designation under which the dispute was to be determined in a court of another State; (e) the judgment is inconsistent with a judgment of the requested State in a dispute between the same parties; (f) the judgment is inconsistent with an earlier judgment of another State between the same parties on the same subject matter, provided the earlier judgment fulfils conditions for recognition in the requested State. Art 7(2): recognition or enforcement may also be postponed or refused where proceedings between the same parties on the same subject matter are pending before a court of the requested State (where that court was seised first and there is a close connection between the dispute and the requested State).",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2019 provides six mandatory grounds for refusal plus a discretionary lis pendens ground — they mirror Hague 2005 but add fraud (not limited to procedure), sovereignty/security in the public policy ground, and a pending proceedings discretion."},
  {id:137,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 8",subtopic:"Preliminary questions",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 8",question:"How does Hague 2019 treat rulings on excluded matters that arise as preliminary questions?",answer:"Art 8(1): a ruling on a preliminary question shall not be recognised or enforced if the ruling is on a matter to which the Convention does not apply, or on an immovable property matter under Art 6 where a court of a State other than the State of the situs ruled. Art 8(2): recognition or enforcement of a judgment may be refused if, and to the extent that, the judgment was based on a ruling on such an excluded matter.",keyPrinciple:"Preliminary rulings on excluded matters are not enforceable under Hague 2019 — and a judgment based on such a ruling may be refused to the extent it rests on the excluded question."},
  {id:138,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 9",subtopic:"Severability",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 9",question:"What does Hague 2019 provide regarding severability of judgments?",answer:"Art 9: recognition or enforcement of a severable part of a judgment shall be granted where recognition or enforcement of that part is applied for, or where only part of the judgment is capable of being recognised or enforced under the Convention.",keyPrinciple:"Hague 2019 allows partial recognition — where only part of a judgment satisfies the Convention's requirements, that severable part may be enforced even if the rest cannot."},
  {id:139,number:"Hague 2019 – Art 10",subtopic:"Damages",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Statute"],flags:[],reference:"Hague Convention 2019, Art 10",question:"What does Hague 2019 provide regarding recognition or enforcement of judgments awarding non-compensatory damages?",answer:"Art 10(1): recognition or enforcement of a judgment may be refused if, and to the extent that, the judgment awards damages — including exemplary or punitive damages — that do not compensate a party for actual loss or harm suffered. Art 10(2): the court addressed shall take into account whether and to what extent the damages awarded by the court of origin serve to cover costs and expenses relating to the proceedings.",keyPrinciple:"Art 10 mirrors Hague 2005 Art 11 — non-compensatory punitive damages may be refused, but the court must consider whether part of the award covers costs before refusing enforcement of the whole."},
  {id:140,number:"Dicey Ill. 1 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Fixed sum requirement",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-048] (Ill. 1) · Suggested by Sadler v Robins (1808) 1 Camp. 253",question:"A recovers judgment against X in a Jamaican court that X should pay A £3,000, after first deducting X's costs, to be taxed by the proper officer. The costs have not yet been taxed. Is the judgment enforceable in England?",answer:"No. The judgment is not a judgment for a fixed sum of money, because the net amount payable depends on a taxation of costs that has not yet been carried out. Under Rule 46(1)(a), enforcement by action requires a judgment for a debt or definite sum of money, actually ascertained. A claim on this judgment is not maintainable.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment is enforceable only if it is for a definite, actually ascertained sum of money — a judgment requiring further assessment (such as untaxed costs) fails this requirement."},
  {id:141,number:"Dicey Ill. 2 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Penal law rule",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-048] (Ill. 2) · cf. US v Inkley [1989] Q.B. 255 (CA)",question:"X, a British subject, is arrested in Florida on fraud charges. He is released on bail on condition he enters into an 'appearance bond', is given permission to leave the United States for thirty days, but fails to return. The United States Government obtains a judgment on the bond in a civil action. Is the judgment enforceable in England?",answer:"No. Although the judgment on the bond is technically civil, no claim on it is maintainable because the purpose of the claim is the enforcement of the criminal process. Under Rule 46(1)(a), a foreign judgment is not enforceable if it is in respect of a fine or other penalty. A penalty in this context includes sums payable to the State as part of the criminal process, even where the form of the judgment is civil.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment is unenforceable if its substance amounts to the enforcement of the criminal process, regardless of the civil form of the proceedings."},
  {id:142,number:"Dicey Ill. 3 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Compensatory element in criminal proceedings",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-049] (Ill. 3) · Raulin v Fischer [1911] 2 K.B. 93",question:"X, while recklessly galloping her horse in a foreign country, ran into A and seriously injured him. X was prosecuted for criminal negligence and A intervened in the prosecution claiming damages as allowed by the foreign law. The court convicted X, fined her 100 francs, and ordered her to pay 15,000 francs to A by way of damages, and also costs. Can A recover the damages and costs in England?",answer:"Yes. A is entitled to recover the sterling equivalent of the damages and costs in England. Although the judgment was given in criminal proceedings, the award of damages to A is compensatory in character and payable to a private claimant, not the State. The fine (100 francs) is penal and unenforceable, but the damages element (15,000 francs) is severable and enforceable under Rule 46(1)(a).",keyPrinciple:"Where a foreign criminal court awards both a fine and compensatory damages to a private party, the damages element is severable and enforceable in England."},
  {id:143,number:"Dicey Ill. 4 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Final and conclusive — remate judgment",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-049] (Ill. 4) · Nouvion v Freeman (1889) 15 App. Cas. 1",question:"A took summary ('executive') proceedings against X in a Spanish court for the recovery of a debt, obtaining a 'remate' judgment for £10,000. In these proceedings X could set up only limited defences and could not dispute the validity of the underlying contract. Either party could take plenary proceedings in the same court in which all defences could be raised. In plenary proceedings, the remate judgment could not be set up as res judicata, and a plenary judgment would render it inoperative. Is the remate judgment enforceable in England?",answer:"No. The remate judgment was not final and conclusive within the meaning of Rule 46(1)(b). A judgment is not final if it may be reviewed or revised by the same court which gave it. Because either party could commence plenary proceedings in which all defences might be raised, and a plenary judgment would render the remate judgment inoperative, the remate judgment did not finally settle the parties' rights. No action was maintainable on it.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment is not final and conclusive if it may be superseded by plenary proceedings in the same court in which all defences can be raised."},
  {id:144,number:"Dicey Ill. 5 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Pending appeal — no bar to enforcement",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-050] (Ill. 5) · Colt Industries Inc v Sarlie (No.2) [1966] 1 W.L.R. 1287",question:"A recovers judgment against X in New York for the equivalent of £900,000. X appeals to the New York Court of Appeals. An appeal under the law of New York is not a stay of execution. While the appeal is pending A brings a claim in England on the judgment. Is the claim maintainable?",answer:"Yes. The claim is maintainable. A judgment which is subject to appeal to a higher court is nevertheless final and conclusive for the purposes of Rule 46(1)(b). The distinction is between review by the same court (which negates finality) and appeal to a higher court (which does not). It is immaterial that the judgment may not be enforceable in other American States until the appeal has been dismissed.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment subject to appeal to a higher court remains final and conclusive — only the possibility of review by the same court negates finality."},
  {id:145,number:"Dicey Ill. 6 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Set aside on appeal — English default judgment",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-050] (Ill. 6) · Merchant International Co Ltd v Natsionalna Aktsionerna Kompaniia Naftogaz [2012] EWCA Civ 196",question:"X obtains a judgment against A in Ukraine. A brings an enforcement action in England and obtains a default judgment for the debt. The Ukrainian judgment is then set aside on appeal and a new Ukrainian trial ordered, although without decisive new evidence and in circumstances inconsistent with the principle of legal certainty under Art. 6 ECHR. A applies to the English court to set aside the English default judgment. Should the application succeed?",answer:"No. The application is refused. The Ukrainian judgment was final and conclusive at the time the English judgment was issued, notwithstanding the subsequent appeal. The discretion to set aside the English default judgment will not be exercised on the basis of a foreign appellate judgment which was obtained in breach of Art. 6 ECHR.",keyPrinciple:"An English default judgment on a foreign judgment will not be set aside merely because the foreign judgment was later reversed on appeal in circumstances inconsistent with Art. 6 ECHR."},
  {id:146,number:"Dicey Ill. 7 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Final and conclusive — firm not personally bound",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-050] (Ill. 7) · Blohn v Desser [1962] 2 Q.B. 116",question:"X, resident in England, was a sleeping partner in a firm carrying on business in Vienna. A obtained judgment against the firm in Vienna on a bill of exchange. By Austrian law, the firm had no separate legal personality and the judgment was not enforceable against the partners personally unless a further action was brought against them individually. A brings an action in England against X on the judgment. Is it maintainable?",answer:"No. The action was not maintainable because the Austrian judgment against the firm was not final and conclusive as against X personally. Under Austrian law, a separate action was required to enforce the judgment against individual partners, and various personal defences would have been available to X. The judgment against the firm did not create a personal obligation binding on X.",keyPrinciple:"A judgment against an entity without separate legal personality is not final and conclusive against individual partners where the foreign law requires a further action to bind them personally."},
  {id:147,number:"Dicey Ill. 8 (Enforcement)",subtopic:"Final and conclusive — variable maintenance order",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-050] (Ill. 8) · Harrop v Harrop [1920] 3 K.B. 386",question:"W obtains a maintenance order against H in a foreign court. The court has power under its law to vary the amount of the payments, both in respect of past and future instalments. Can W bring a claim in England on the judgment of the foreign court?",answer:"No. W cannot bring a claim in England on the judgment, because the maintenance order is not final and conclusive. The foreign court retains power to vary the amount of payments (both past and future), so the judgment sum has not been finally fixed. A judgment whose quantum remains open to variation by the court which awarded it fails the finality requirement under Rule 46(1)(b).",keyPrinciple:"A maintenance order whose quantum may be varied by the court that made it is not final and conclusive and cannot be enforced by action in England."},
  {id:148,number:"Dicey Ill. 9 (Recognition)",subtopic:"Defence to English claim",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-051] (Ill. 9) · CJJA 1982, s.34; cf. Plummer v Woodburne (1825) 4 B. & C. 625",question:"A brings an action in a Victorian court against X for breach of contract. X denies the breach. A judgment which is final and conclusive in Victoria is given in favour of X. A then sues X in England for the same breach of contract. Can X rely on the Victorian judgment?",answer:"Yes. The Victorian judgment is a defence to A's claim in England against X for the same breach of contract. Under Rule 46(2), a foreign judgment which satisfies the requirements for recognition operates as res judicata between the parties. By virtue of CJJA 1982, s.34, where a foreign judgment has been given on a matter, no proceedings may be brought by a party to the foreign proceedings on the same cause of action.",keyPrinciple:"A final and conclusive foreign judgment in favour of the defendant operates as a defence (cause of action estoppel) to subsequent English proceedings on the same claim."},
  {id:149,number:"Dicey Ill. 10 (Recognition)",subtopic:"Foreign limitation — not a defence today",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-051] (Ill. 10) · Harris v Quine (1869) L.R. 4 Q.B. 653; Foreign Limitation Periods Act 1984, s.3",question:"In 1865 A brought an action against X in the Isle of Man to recover a debt. Under a Manx statute, no action could be brought to recover a debt more than three years after the cause of action accrued, but the statute did not extinguish the debt. The Manx court gave judgment for X on the ground that the action was statute-barred. A then sued X for the debt in England. Was the Manx judgment a defence?",answer:"At the time, the Manx judgment was not a defence to the action in England, because English law treated limitation as procedural and the Manx statute merely barred the remedy without extinguishing the debt. But today it would be a defence, because under the Foreign Limitation Periods Act 1984, s.3, foreign limitation periods are now treated as substantive, so the Manx judgment on limitation would be recognised as deciding the merits.",keyPrinciple:"Since the Foreign Limitation Periods Act 1984, a foreign judgment dismissing a claim on limitation grounds is treated as deciding the merits and operates as a defence in England."},
  {id:150,number:"Dicey Ill. 11 (Recognition)",subtopic:"Res judicata — priority of competing judgments",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-051] (Ill. 11) · Showlag v Mansour [1995] 1 A.C. 431 (PC)",question:"A sues X in England for return of a sum of money and obtains judgment that X was a constructive trustee. The English judgment is recognised in Jersey, and X's defence is struck out. An Egyptian court later gives a judgment that X received the money as a gift, not as trustee. X applies to amend his defence in the Jersey proceedings, contending that the Egyptian judgment is res judicata. Which judgment does the Jersey court recognise?",answer:"The Jersey court recognises the English judgment (being the first in time) and therefore not the Egyptian judgment. Where two foreign judgments both qualify in principle for recognition in a jurisdiction and they are inconsistent, the court will recognise the first judgment given, and will not give effect to the later inconsistent judgment.",keyPrinciple:"Where two inconsistent foreign judgments both qualify for recognition, the first in time prevails."},
  {id:151,number:"Dicey Ill. 12 (Recognition)",subtopic:"Issue estoppel — identity of parties",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-052] (Ill. 12) · Carl Zeiss Stiftung v Rayner & Keeler Ltd (No.2) [1967] 1 A.C. 853",question:"In proceedings by the Zeiss Foundation of East Germany against X in England, X denies the authority of Zeiss's solicitors to bring the action, relying in part on a decision of a West German court in proceedings between Zeiss and X that Zeiss was not properly before the West German court because the East German organ which purported to act on its behalf had no authority. Does the West German decision give rise to an issue estoppel?",answer:"No. The decision of the West German court does not give rise to an issue estoppel because there is no identity of parties or identity of interest. The relevant parties in the English proceedings on the issue of authority are X and Zeiss's solicitors, not X and Zeiss. Issue estoppel requires that the parties (or their privies) in both proceedings be the same.",keyPrinciple:"Issue estoppel from a foreign judgment requires identity of parties or their privies — it does not arise where the relevant parties in the two sets of proceedings differ."},
  {id:152,number:"Dicey Ill. 13 (Recognition)",subtopic:"Issue estoppel — jurisdictional determination",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-052] (Ill. 13) · The Sennar (No. 2) [1985] 1 W.L.R. 490 (HL)",question:"A sues X in the Netherlands. The Dutch court decides that the parties have agreed that the dispute should be heard exclusively by the Sudanese courts. A then sues X in England. Is A bound by the Dutch court's determination on the applicability of the jurisdiction clause?",answer:"Yes. A is bound by the determination of the Dutch court on the issue of the applicability of the jurisdiction clause. The Dutch judgment on this point was a decision 'on the merits' for the purposes of issue estoppel — it established facts, identified applicable legal principles, and reached a conclusion on the effect of the jurisdiction clause. This is a classic case of issue estoppel from a foreign court of competent jurisdiction.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign court's determination on the applicability of a jurisdiction clause is a decision 'on the merits' capable of giving rise to issue estoppel in subsequent English proceedings."},
  {id:153,number:"Dicey Ill. 14 (Recognition)",subtopic:"Cause of action estoppel — scope of foreign judgment",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-052] (Ill. 14)",question:"H, an Englishman, is killed in Spain by the negligent driving of X. W, his widow, gives a power of attorney to a Spanish lawyer to represent her and their children in Spanish criminal proceedings (in which civil damages may also be awarded). The Spanish lawyer fails to reserve the right under Spanish law to seek damages elsewhere. The Spanish court orders X to pay damages. In a subsequent action in England, can W sue (a) on her own behalf, (b) on behalf of the estate, and (c) on behalf of the children?",answer:"(a) No — W cannot sue on her own behalf because the English proceedings are brought on a cause of action in respect of which the Spanish judgment has already been given; the foreign judgment precludes the same cause of action being relitigated. (b) Yes — she can sue on behalf of the estate, because no claim on behalf of the estate was made in the Spanish proceedings; there is no prior judgment on that cause of action. (c) Yes — she can sue on behalf of the children, because the actions taken on their behalf in Spain were contrary to their interests, and there was no evidence that they were able to give informed consent to the power of attorney. They are not bound by the Spanish judgment.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment precludes re-litigation only of those causes of action actually determined; claims by different parties or in different capacities not advanced in the foreign proceedings remain open."},
  {id:154,number:"Dicey Ill. 15 (Recognition)",subtopic:"Issue estoppel — different parties and issues",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-052] (Ill. 15)",question:"X brings an action in New York against A Ltd in tort. A Ltd argues that the proceedings should be stayed in favour of the courts of Tanzania. B Ltd, a wholly owned subsidiary of A Ltd, commences proceedings against X in the English courts in contract. Does any issue estoppel arise?",answer:"No. No issue estoppel arises, for two independent reasons. First, the proceedings do not involve the same parties or their privies — B Ltd (a subsidiary) is a separate legal entity from A Ltd. Second, the question of which forum is most appropriate for the claim in tort is a distinct issue from the question of which is most appropriate for the claim in contract.",keyPrinciple:"Issue estoppel requires both identity of parties (or privies) and identity of the issue decided — a subsidiary is not a privy of its parent, and forum questions for distinct claims are distinct issues."},
  {id:155,number:"Dicey Ill. 16 (Preclusion)",subtopic:"Merger — partial payment of judgment debt",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-053] (Ill. 16)",question:"A brings an action in New York against X, a resident of New York, and recovers judgment for $100,000. Part of the judgment debt is paid by X. A then brings a claim in England against X for the same debt. Will the claim succeed?",answer:"No. The claim on the underlying debt will fail. The cause of action on the debt has merged into the New York judgment; A cannot sue again on the original cause of action. A's remedy is to enforce the balance of the judgment — i.e. to bring an action on the judgment itself for the unpaid portion.",keyPrinciple:"Where a foreign judgment has been given on a debt, the original cause of action merges into the judgment — the creditor's remedy is to enforce the judgment, not to re-sue on the underlying debt."},
  {id:156,number:"Dicey Ill. 17 (Preclusion)",subtopic:"Merger — disappointed claimant",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 46 [14-053] (Ill. 17)",question:"A brings proceedings in New York against X and recovers judgment for $100,000, which is far less than she had claimed. She later brings a claim in England against X in respect of the same cause of action, giving credit for the $100,000 already recovered. Must the English proceedings be struck out?",answer:"Yes. In the absence of grounds for an estoppel or the like, the proceedings must be struck out. A foreign judgment on a cause of action precludes the claimant from bringing a fresh action in England on the same cause of action, even where the claimant recovered less than she had hoped and offers to give credit for the amount already awarded. The cause of action has been finally determined.",keyPrinciple:"A disappointed claimant who recovers less than expected in foreign proceedings cannot re-litigate the same cause of action in England, even giving credit for the foreign award."},
  {id:157,number:"Dicey Ill. 1 (Jurisdiction — First Case)",subtopic:"Presence — corporate presence and submission",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-098] (Ill. 1) · Adams v Cape Industries Plc [1990] Ch. 433 (CA)",question:"462 individuals bring personal injury actions in Texas against X & Co (an English holding company), Y & Co (an English marketing subsidiary), and Z & Co (an Illinois corporation). X & Co and Y & Co object to jurisdiction but the actions settle under a consent order. Subsequently, 206 more individuals commence similar proceedings; X & Co, Y & Co, and Z & Co take no part. Z & Co ceases business and its US marketing is carried on by two new subsidiaries of X & Co (one in Illinois, one in Liechtenstein). Default judgments are entered. Are the default judgments recognisable in England?",answer:"The default judgments are not recognised because, among other reasons, the federal court in Texas has no jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement purposes in England. The consent order in the first set of actions amounted to submission to the jurisdiction for those actions, but not for the second set. Whether or not presence in Illinois was sufficient for enforcement of the judgment of a Federal court sitting in Texas, X & Co and Y & Co were not present in Illinois through their Illinois subsidiaries. Corporate presence requires more than the existence of a subsidiary; the subsidiary must be carrying on the parent's business, not its own.",keyPrinciple:"A parent company is not present in a foreign jurisdiction merely through a subsidiary — the subsidiary must be carrying on the parent's fixed place of business, not its own independent business."},
  {id:158,number:"Dicey Ill. 2 (Jurisdiction — First Case)",subtopic:"Presence — transient presence",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-098] (Ill. 2) · Carrick v Hancock (1895) 12 T.L.R. 59",question:"X, an English traveller, is staying for a few days in a hotel in Massachusetts when a summons commencing an action against him is served upon him in the Massachusetts court. Does the Massachusetts court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement purposes in England?",answer:"Yes. The Massachusetts court has jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England. Under the First Case of Rule 47, a foreign court has jurisdiction if the person against whom the judgment was given was present in the foreign country when the proceedings were instituted. Even transient or temporary presence suffices — there is no requirement of residence.",keyPrinciple:"Even transient presence in the foreign country at the time of service is sufficient to found jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England."},
  {id:159,number:"Dicey Ill. 3 (Jurisdiction — First Case)",subtopic:"Presence — service on director of foreign company",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-098] (Ill. 3) · Littauer Glove Corp v FW Millington (1920) Ltd (1928) 44 T.L.R. 746",question:"Y is the director of X & Co, an English company. Y visits New York and while he is there A, a New York firm, takes out a summons against X & Co and serves process upon Y. X & Co has no branch in New York and does not carry on business there. Is the New York court's judgment entitled to recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"No. The judgment of the New York court is not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. Service of process on a director of a company while he is personally present in the jurisdiction does not make the company present there. X & Co had no branch in New York and did not carry on business there. The company itself was not present in the jurisdiction when the proceedings were commenced.",keyPrinciple:"Service on a company's director who happens to be present in the foreign jurisdiction does not make the company itself present there for the purposes of jurisdictional competence."},
  {id:160,number:"Dicey Ill. 4 (Jurisdiction — First Case)",subtopic:"Presence — representative without authority",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-098] (Ill. 4) · Vogel v RA Kohnstamm Ltd [1973] Q.B. 133",question:"X & Co, an English company, employs Y, a resident of Israel, as its representative there to elicit orders from customers. Y has no authority from X & Co to make contracts on its behalf. Y introduces an Israeli customer A, who contracts with X & Co for the purchase of goods. A sues X & Co in Israel for breach of contract. X & Co takes no part in the proceedings and has no office or place of business in Israel. Is the Israeli court's judgment entitled to recognition and enforcement?",answer:"No. The judgment of the Israeli court is not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. X & Co was not present in Israel through Y, because Y was not carrying on X & Co's business in Israel — Y had no authority to make contracts on X & Co's behalf. A representative who merely solicits orders without binding authority does not establish the company's presence in the jurisdiction.",keyPrinciple:"A company is not present in a foreign jurisdiction through a representative who merely solicits orders without authority to contract on the company's behalf."},
  {id:161,number:"Dicey Ill. 5 (Jurisdiction — Second Case)",subtopic:"Submission as claimant",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 5)",question:"A, an Englishman residing in England, brings an action against X in Tel Aviv for breach of a contract made and broken in England. The court gives judgment for costs against A. Does the Israeli court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement purposes in England?",answer:"Yes. The Israeli court has jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England. Under the Second Case of Rule 47, a foreign court has jurisdiction if the person against whom the judgment was given was the claimant (or counterclaimant) in the foreign proceedings. By bringing the action in Tel Aviv, A submitted to the jurisdiction of the Israeli court, including for the purposes of any adverse costs order.",keyPrinciple:"A person who brings proceedings in a foreign court as claimant thereby submits to the jurisdiction of that court, including for any costs order made against him."},
  {id:162,number:"Dicey Ill. 6 (Jurisdiction — Second Case)",subtopic:"Submission by counterclaim",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 6) · GFH Capital Ltd v Haigh [2020] EWHC 1269 (Comm.)",question:"A brings proceedings against X in the courts of Dubai. X counterclaims in those proceedings unsuccessfully, and A obtains a judgment against X. Do the courts of Dubai have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"Yes. The courts of Dubai have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England. Under the Second Case of Rule 47, the judgment debtor submitted to the jurisdiction by counterclaiming in the foreign proceedings. A counterclaimant, like a claimant, invokes the court's jurisdiction and thereby submits to it.",keyPrinciple:"Filing a counterclaim in foreign proceedings constitutes submission to the jurisdiction of the foreign court for recognition and enforcement purposes."},
  {id:163,number:"Dicey Ill. 7 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Voluntary appearance",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 7) · cf. Voinet v Barrett (1885) 55 L.J.Q.B. 39 (CA)",question:"A brings an action in a New York court against X, an Englishwoman. X appears and defends the action because her business transactions frequently involve her presence in New York, so that judgment might be executed against her there. Her appearance is voluntary. Does the New York court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"Yes. The New York court has jurisdiction over X for the purposes of recognition and enforcement in England. Under the Third Case of Rule 47, a foreign court has jurisdiction if the person against whom judgment was given voluntarily appeared in the proceedings. X's motivation for appearing (to protect her business interests) does not prevent the appearance from being voluntary.",keyPrinciple:"A voluntary appearance to defend foreign proceedings constitutes submission to the jurisdiction, regardless of the defendant's commercial motivation for appearing."},
  {id:164,number:"Dicey Ill. 8 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Appearance after default to recover property",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 8) · cf. Guiard v De Clermont [1914] 3 K.B. 145",question:"The circumstances are the same as Illustration 7 (action in New York against an Englishwoman), except that X does not appear until after judgment has been given in default and execution has been levied. X then appears and secures the reopening of the proceedings in order to recover property upon which execution has been levied. Does the New York court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"Yes. The New York court has jurisdiction for the purposes of recognition and enforcement in England. Although X appeared only after default judgment and execution, her appearance to reopen the proceedings goes beyond merely protesting the jurisdiction — she invoked the court's jurisdiction to recover property. This constitutes voluntary submission.",keyPrinciple:"Appearing in foreign proceedings after a default judgment in order to reopen the case and recover property constitutes voluntary submission to the jurisdiction."},
  {id:165,number:"Dicey Ill. 9 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Appearance — appeal not on jurisdictional grounds",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 9) · SA Consortium General Textiles v Sun & Sand Agencies Ltd [1978] Q.B. 279 (CA)",question:"A brings an action in a foreign court against X and obtains a judgment against X in default of appearance. X's application to the foreign court for leave to appeal out of time is dismissed, but X also appeals to the Court of Appeal for the relevant district on the basis that he was not in fact out of time to appeal. The appeal is not expressed to be on jurisdictional grounds. Does the foreign court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"Yes. The foreign court has jurisdiction for the purposes of recognition and enforcement in England. X's appeal was not expressed to be on jurisdictional grounds — it was on the substantive question of whether the appeal was out of time. An appeal which does not contest jurisdiction constitutes voluntary appearance and submission to the foreign court's jurisdiction.",keyPrinciple:"An appeal to a foreign court on non-jurisdictional grounds constitutes submission to the jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement purposes."},
  {id:166,number:"Dicey Ill. 10 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Appearance — jurisdiction founded on arrest of property",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 10) · Guiard v De Clermont [1914] 3 K.B. 145",question:"A brings an action in a foreign country against X, an Englishman, jurisdiction being founded solely upon the arrest of property of X in the country concerned. X appears in order to recover the property arrested. It appears that the judgment of the foreign court is not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. Why?",answer:"It appears that the judgment of the foreign court is not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. Jurisdiction founded solely upon the arrest of property (jurisdiction in rem or quasi in rem) does not give the foreign court in personam jurisdiction over the defendant. X's appearance was solely to recover the arrested property, not to submit to the court's in personam jurisdiction. The arrest of property is not one of the recognised bases of in personam jurisdiction under Rule 47.",keyPrinciple:"Jurisdiction founded solely on the arrest of property does not confer in personam jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement purposes in England."},
  {id:167,number:"Dicey Ill. 11 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Conditional appearance becoming unconditional",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 11) · CJJA 1982, s.33(1)(a)",question:"A brings an action against X in a foreign court. X enters a conditional appearance in order to contest the jurisdiction. The conditional appearance becomes unconditional automatically when X's application to contest the jurisdiction fails, but X takes no further part in the proceedings. Is the judgment entitled to recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"No. The judgment is not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. Under CJJA 1982, s.33(1)(a), a person shall not be regarded as having submitted to the jurisdiction of a foreign court by reason only of having entered a conditional appearance (however described) to contest the jurisdiction. The fact that the conditional appearance became unconditional by operation of the foreign procedural law does not convert what was in substance a jurisdictional challenge into voluntary submission.",keyPrinciple:"Under s.33(1)(a) CJJA 1982, entering a conditional appearance to contest jurisdiction does not constitute submission, even if the appearance becomes unconditional under the foreign court's procedure."},
  {id:168,number:"Dicey Ill. 12 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Application to set aside on forum conveniens",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 12) · CJJA 1982, s.33(1)(b)",question:"A brings an action against X in a foreign court. X applies to the foreign court to set aside the proceedings on the grounds that the foreign court is not the forum conveniens. The application fails. Is the judgment entitled to recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"No. The judgment of the foreign court is not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. Under CJJA 1982, s.33(1)(b), a person shall not be regarded as having submitted to the jurisdiction of a foreign court by reason only of having asked the court to dismiss or stay the proceedings on the ground that the dispute should be submitted to arbitration or to the determination of the courts of another country. An application on forum non conveniens grounds falls within this provision.",keyPrinciple:"Under s.33(1)(b) CJJA 1982, applying to a foreign court to stay or dismiss proceedings on forum non conveniens grounds does not constitute submission to jurisdiction."},
  {id:169,number:"Dicey Ill. 13 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Jurisdictional challenge — merits heard together",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 13) · See AES Ust-Kamenogorsk Hydropower Plant LLP v AES Ust-Kamenogorsk Hydropower Plant JSC [2013] UKSC 35",question:"A brings an action against X in a foreign court. X applies to challenge the jurisdiction, but the court decides to hear the merits of the claim together with the jurisdictional challenge, giving a ruling on the merits only if it concludes there is jurisdiction. X calls evidence. The court rules it has jurisdiction and gives judgment on the merits in favour of A. X's purpose in appearing was to contest the jurisdiction. Will the judgment, in principle at least, be recognised?",answer:"In principle at least, the judgment against X will not be recognised. X's purpose in appearing before the foreign court was to contest the jurisdiction. The fact that the foreign court chose to hear the merits simultaneously with the jurisdictional challenge does not convert X's appearance into voluntary submission. X did not voluntarily submit to the court's jurisdiction on the merits; the court's procedural choice to hear both matters together should not prejudice X's position.",keyPrinciple:"Where a defendant appears in foreign proceedings solely to contest jurisdiction and the foreign court chooses to hear the merits simultaneously, the appearance does not in principle constitute voluntary submission."},
  {id:170,number:"Dicey Ill. 14 (Jurisdiction — Third Case)",subtopic:"Submission — uninformed consumer",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-099] (Ill. 14) · cf. CJJA 1982, s.15B(3) and s.15D(4)",question:"A, domiciled in England, enters into a consumer contract with X, a New York company. X commences proceedings against A in New York. A is notified of the proceedings and responds by challenging the merits of the claim, without understanding or being advised that this constitutes submission to the New York court. The New York court gives judgment against A. Will the judgment be entitled to recognition or enforcement in England?",answer:"It appears that the judgment will not be entitled to recognition or enforcement in England. By analogy with CJJA 1982, s.15B(3) and s.15D(4), a consumer who responds to foreign proceedings on the merits without understanding that this constitutes submission, and without being advised of this consequence, should not be treated as having voluntarily submitted to the jurisdiction. This may be viewed as a particular application of Rule 54 (natural justice).",keyPrinciple:"A consumer who responds to foreign proceedings on the merits without understanding or being advised that this amounts to submission may not be treated as having voluntarily submitted to the foreign court's jurisdiction."},
  {id:171,number:"Dicey Ill. 15 (Jurisdiction — Fourth Case)",subtopic:"Contractual submission — jurisdiction clause",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-101] (Ill. 15) · cf. Feyerick v Hubbard (1902) 71 L.J.K.B. 509",question:"A is a New York firm carrying on business in New York. X is a British citizen resident in England. By a contract made in New York, X agrees to assign certain patent rights to A, the contract providing that 'all disputes as to the present agreement and its fulfilment shall be submitted to the New York jurisdiction.' In an action by A in the appropriate New York court for breach of the contract, judgment is given for A for $1 million. Does the New York court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"Yes. The New York court has jurisdiction for the purposes of recognition and enforcement in England. Under the Fourth Case of Rule 47, a foreign court has jurisdiction if the person against whom judgment was given had, before the commencement of proceedings, agreed to submit to the jurisdiction of that court. The clause providing that all disputes shall be submitted to the New York jurisdiction constitutes such an agreement.",keyPrinciple:"A contractual clause submitting all disputes to the jurisdiction of a specified foreign court constitutes prior agreement to submit under the Fourth Case of Rule 47."},
  {id:172,number:"Dicey Ill. 16 (Jurisdiction — Fourth Case)",subtopic:"Contractual submission — articles of association (effective)",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-101] (Ill. 16) · Copin v Adamson (1874) L.R. 9 Ex. 345 (first replication)",question:"X, resident in England, held shares in a French company. The statutes or articles of association of the company provided that every dispute should be subject to the jurisdiction of the French courts and that every shareholder must 'elect a domicile' in France for service of process (and that in default the officers of the company might do so for him). X never elected a domicile. The company went into liquidation and A brought an action in France against X for moneys not paid up on X's shares. Notice was duly served on X at his statutory domicile. X had no knowledge of the proceedings. Judgment was given against X. Does the French court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"Yes. The French court had jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England. By subscribing for shares and thereby binding himself to the articles of association, X agreed to submit disputes with the company to the jurisdiction of the French courts. The articles constituted a contractual agreement to submit under the Fourth Case of Rule 47. The fact that X did not actually elect a domicile or have knowledge of the proceedings does not negate the jurisdictional agreement.",keyPrinciple:"By subscribing for shares in a foreign company whose articles contain a jurisdiction clause, a shareholder contractually agrees to submit to the jurisdiction of the specified courts."},
  {id:173,number:"Dicey Ill. 17 (Jurisdiction — Fourth Case)",subtopic:"Contractual submission — general provisions insufficient",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-101] (Ill. 17) · Copin v Adamson (second replication); contrast Vallée v Dumergue (1849) 4 Exch. 290",question:"The circumstances are the same as the previous illustration (shareholder in a French company), except that the provisions about disputes being referred to the jurisdiction of the French courts and about 'electing a domicile' were general provisions of French law applicable to all French companies, rather than specific terms of the company's articles of association. Is the judgment of the French court entitled to recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"No. The judgment of the French court was not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. General provisions of French law imposing jurisdiction on all shareholders of French companies do not constitute an agreement by X to submit to French jurisdiction. The Fourth Case of Rule 47 requires an actual agreement to submit — not a deemed submission imposed by the general law of the foreign country. The critical distinction is between a contractual agreement (in the articles themselves) and a statutory imposition.",keyPrinciple:"General provisions of foreign law imposing jurisdiction over all shareholders of foreign companies do not constitute an agreement to submit — the Fourth Case requires actual contractual agreement."},
  {id:174,number:"Dicey Ill. 18 (Jurisdiction — Fourth Case)",subtopic:"Contractual submission — statutory agent",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-101] (Ill. 18) · Bank of Australasia v Harding (1850) 9 C.B. 661",question:"X, who is resident in England, is a member of an Australian company. By an Australian statute referring to this particular company, the chairman of the company is capable of suing or being sued in place of the company and may act and be treated as the agent of the members. A recovers judgment against the chairman, and therefore against (inter alios) X, in an action in an Australian court of which X has no notice. Does the Australian court have jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"Yes. The Australian court has jurisdiction for the purposes of recognition and enforcement in England. By becoming a member of the company, X agreed to be bound by the statute under which the chairman could be sued as agent of the members. This amounts to an agreement to submit to the jurisdiction of the Australian court through the statutory mechanism.",keyPrinciple:"Joining a company whose governing statute designates the chairman as agent for suit on behalf of members constitutes agreement to submit to the jurisdiction of the courts where the company is established."},
  {id:175,number:"Dicey Ill. 19 (Jurisdiction — Fourth Case)",subtopic:"No submission — former resident/partner",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-101] (Ill. 19) · Emanuel v Symon [1908] 1 K.B. 302 (CA)",question:"X, a British citizen, when resident and carrying on business in Western Australia, entered into partnership with A for the working of a gold mine there. The partnership was dissolved and an account was taken under decree of a Western Australian court. A deficiency appearing, A sued X in the same court. X had ceased to be resident in Western Australia and the writ was served upon him in England. X did not appear. Is the judgment of the Western Australian court entitled to recognition and enforcement in England?",answer:"No. The judgment of the Western Australian court is not entitled to recognition and enforcement in England. X was not present in Western Australia when the proceedings were commenced, did not submit by appearance, was not the claimant, and had not agreed to submit to the jurisdiction. The fact that X was formerly resident and carried on business there, and that the dispute arose from activities there, is insufficient to establish jurisdiction under any of the four cases in Rule 47.",keyPrinciple:"Former residence or business activity in the foreign country does not establish jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement — the defendant must be present, have submitted, or have agreed to submit at the relevant time."},
  {id:176,number:"Dicey Ill. 20 (Jurisdiction — Fourth Case)",subtopic:"No implied agreement to submit",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 47 [14-101] (Ill. 20) · Vizcaya Partners Ltd v Picard [2016] UKPC 5",question:"A commences proceedings against X, a company registered in the British Virgin Islands, in New York, pursuant to a contract which does not contain a jurisdiction agreement, but contains a choice of New York law and a clause deeming the contract to have been made in New York and establishing obligations to be performed in New York. Is the judgment of the New York court entitled to recognition and enforcement at common law?",answer:"No. Although consent to the jurisdiction of the New York courts may in principle be based on an implied agreement, there is insufficient evidence that an agreement in favour of the New York courts was implied either as a matter of fact or New York law. A choice of law clause, a deemed place of making, and obligations to be performed in New York do not, without more, amount to an implied agreement to submit to the jurisdiction of the New York courts. The judgment cannot be recognised or enforced at common law.",keyPrinciple:"An agreement to submit to a foreign court's jurisdiction must generally be express — a choice of law clause and obligations to be performed in that jurisdiction do not, without more, imply an agreement to submit."},
  {id:177,number:"Dicey Ill. 1 (Conclusiveness)",subtopic:"Error of foreign law — judgment conclusive",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 51 [14-123] (Ill. 1) · Godard v Gray (1870) L.R. 6 Q.B. 139",question:"A sued X in a French court for breach of an English charterparty, in which was a clause 'penalty for the non-performance of this agreement, estimated amount of freight.' The foreign court, under an erroneous view of the English law, treated this clause as fixing the amount of damages recoverable, and gave judgment in favour of A for £700, the amount of the freight. Is the judgment conclusive?",answer:"Yes. The judgment, though given under a mistaken view of the English law, is conclusive. Under Rule 51, the merits of a foreign judgment given by a court of competent jurisdiction are not open to re-examination in England. An English court will not inquire into whether the foreign court correctly applied the relevant law, even where the foreign court erroneously construed English law. The rule against review on the merits is absolute.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment is conclusive on the merits even if the foreign court applied the governing law incorrectly — English courts will not review the merits."},
  {id:178,number:"Dicey Ill. 2 (Conclusiveness)",subtopic:"Error of its own law — judgment conclusive",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 51 [14-123] (Ill. 2) · Scott v Pilkington (1862) 2 B. & S. 11",question:"A brings an action in England for £200 due to A from X under a judgment of a New York court. The judgment is founded on a mistaken view of the law of New York. Is the judgment conclusive?",answer:"Yes. The judgment is conclusive. It does not matter whether the foreign court's error was in applying its own law or a foreign law. The rule against review on the merits applies equally whether the foreign court misapplied its own law or the law of another country.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment is conclusive on the merits whether the foreign court's error was in applying its own law or a foreign law — no distinction is drawn."},
  {id:179,number:"Dicey Ill. 3 (Conclusiveness)",subtopic:"Available defences not raised",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 51 [14-123] (Ill. 3) · Ellis v M'Henry (1871) L.R. 6 C.P. 228",question:"A obtains a judgment for a debt against X in a Canadian court. X, at the time when the action is brought in Canada, has been made bankrupt in England and might have pleaded his discharge in bankruptcy in defence to the action. The Canadian judgment is sought to be enforced in England. Is it conclusive?",answer:"Yes. The Canadian judgment is conclusive. The fact that X had a potential defence (discharge in bankruptcy) which he might have raised in the Canadian proceedings but did not does not make the judgment less conclusive. A party who fails to raise an available defence in the foreign proceedings cannot raise it as a ground for resisting enforcement in England.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment is conclusive even where the judgment debtor had available defences which he failed to raise in the foreign proceedings."},
  {id:180,number:"Dicey Ill. 4 (Conclusiveness)",subtopic:"Defence deliberately not raised",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 51 [14-124] (Ill. 4) · Israel Discount Bank of New York v Hadjipateras [1984] 1 W.L.R. 137 (CA)",question:"A obtains a judgment on a guarantee against X and Y in a New York court. X seeks to resist enforcement in England on the ground that the guarantee was executed under the undue influence of Y, but X had deliberately refrained from making that allegation in the New York proceedings. Is the judgment conclusive?",answer:"Yes. The judgment is conclusive. A party who deliberately refrains from raising a defence in the foreign proceedings cannot subsequently rely on that defence to resist enforcement in England. The rule against review on the merits is not circumvented by the judgment debtor's tactical decision to withhold a defence.",keyPrinciple:"A judgment debtor who deliberately withholds a defence in the foreign proceedings cannot subsequently rely on it to resist enforcement in England."},
  {id:181,number:"Dicey Ill. 5 (Conclusiveness)",subtopic:"Fresh evidence — foreign appeal refused",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 51 [14-124] (Ill. 5)",question:"A sues X & Co for a debt in a foreign court. X & Co pleads that it has paid the debt but the receipt cannot be found. The court disbelieves the evidence and gives judgment for A. Subsequently, X & Co finds the missing receipt and applies to the foreign court for leave to appeal out of time against the judgment. The foreign court dismisses the application. A brings an action on the judgment against X & Co in England. Will the action succeed?",answer:"It appears that the action will fail. Although the general rule is that a foreign judgment is conclusive on the merits, the discovery of the receipt constitutes fresh evidence that the judgment was obtained in circumstances which would justify its impeachment. The foreign court's refusal of leave to appeal out of time does not preclude the English court from examining the matter, since the English court is not bound by the foreign court's procedural decisions on its own appeal process.",keyPrinciple:"Discovery of decisive fresh evidence after a foreign judgment may provide a basis for resisting enforcement, even where the foreign court refused permission to reopen the case."},
  {id:182,number:"Dicey Ill. 6 (Conclusiveness)",subtopic:"Judgment on a judgment — not enforceable",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 51 [14-124] (Ill. 6) · Strategic Technologies Pte Ltd v Procurement Bureau of the Republic of China Ministry of National Defence [2020] EWCA Civ 1604",question:"A sues X in Singapore and obtains a judgment in its favour. A brings proceedings in the Cayman Islands to enforce the judgment. X submits to the jurisdiction of the Cayman Islands court, which finds that the judgment is enforceable on the (contested) basis that X also submitted to the jurisdiction of the Singapore courts. A seeks to enforce the Cayman Islands judgment in England. Will the English courts enforce it?",answer:"No. The English courts will not enforce the 'judgment on a judgment' of the Cayman Islands. English law does not permit the enforcement of a foreign judgment which is itself merely the enforcement of another foreign judgment. The proper course is to enforce the original Singapore judgment directly in England, applying the English rules on jurisdictional competence independently. The Cayman Islands court's finding on submission to Singapore's jurisdiction does not bind the English court.",keyPrinciple:"English courts will not enforce a 'judgment on a judgment' — a foreign enforcement judgment does not create an independent obligation enforceable in England."},
  {id:183,number:"Dicey Ill. 7 (Conclusiveness)",subtopic:"Foreign refusal to enforce — not res judicata in England",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 51 [14-124] (Ill. 7) · Yukos Capital Sarl v OJC Rosneft Oil Co (No.2) [2012] EWCA Civ 855",question:"A sues X in Russia and the Russian court gives judgment against X. Proceedings brought by A to enforce the judgment in the Netherlands are dismissed, the Dutch court finding that enforcement would be contrary to public policy because the Russian judgment was obtained by a 'partial and dependent' procedure. In proceedings by A to enforce the Russian judgment in England, is the ruling of the Dutch court entitled to recognition as res judicata?",answer:"No. The ruling of the Dutch court against A is not entitled to recognition as res judicata in England. The decision whether the Russian judgment is contrary to English public policy is a distinct matter for the English courts. Each country applies its own public policy standards when determining whether to enforce a foreign judgment. A Dutch court's refusal to enforce on Dutch public policy grounds does not bind the English court on the separate question of English public policy.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign court's refusal to enforce a judgment on public policy grounds does not create a res judicata binding on England — each State applies its own public policy independently."},
  {id:184,number:"Dicey Ill. 1 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — concealment of material fact",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-146] (Ill. 1) · cf. Abouloff v Oppenheimer (1882) 10 Q.B.D. 295 (CA)",question:"A obtains a judgment in a Russian court against X that X shall either deliver to A certain goods or pay A a sum equivalent to £1,050. The judgment, which is affirmed on appeal to a superior Russian court, is obtained by A fraudulently concealing from the court that at the very moment when the action is brought the goods are in the possession of A. Is the judgment impeachable in England?",answer:"Yes. The judgment is impeachable in England on the ground of fraud. A obtained the judgment by fraudulently concealing from the Russian court a material fact — namely, that the goods were already in A's possession. Under Rule 53, a foreign judgment is impeachable if it was obtained by fraud, and this includes fraud consisting of the deliberate concealment of a material fact from the foreign court.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment obtained by the fraudulent concealment of a material fact from the foreign court is impeachable in England."},
  {id:185,number:"Dicey Ill. 2 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — misrepresentation to the court",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-146] (Ill. 2) · cf. Vadala v Lawes (1890) 25 Q.B.D. 310 (CA)",question:"A brings an action in New York against X to recover money alleged to be due on certain bills of exchange. A obtains judgment against X by fraudulently representing to the New York court that the bills of exchange were given under the authority of X and for mercantile transactions, whereas they were given without X's authority for gambling debts. Is the judgment impeachable?",answer:"Yes. The judgment is impeachable in England. A obtained the judgment by positively misrepresenting the nature and authority of the bills of exchange to the New York court. This constitutes fraud on the court. The fraud defence under Rule 53 covers both fraudulent concealment of material facts and affirmative misrepresentation to the foreign court.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment obtained by affirmative misrepresentation to the foreign court about material facts is impeachable for fraud in England."},
  {id:186,number:"Dicey Ill. 3 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — setting aside registration under 1933 Act",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-146] (Ill. 3) · Syal v Heyward [1948] 2 K.B. 443 (CA)",question:"A, an Indian moneylender, obtains judgment against X for 20,000 rupees alleged to be due on a loan. The writ is served upon X in India, but he fails to appear. A registers his judgment in the High Court under the 1933 Act. X applies to set aside the registration on the ground of fraud. X alleges that the amount of the loan was only 10,800 rupees and that A has concealed from the Indian court the possibility that X might have a defence under the Indian Usurious Loans Act. How should the court proceed?",answer:"The court will direct the trial of an issue whether X's allegations are true and, if they are, will set aside the registration of the judgment. A judgment registered under the 1933 Act may be set aside if it was obtained by fraud, just as a judgment enforced at common law may be impeached for fraud. The judgment debtor need only establish a prima facie case of fraud for the court to investigate the allegation.",keyPrinciple:"A judgment registered under the 1933 Act may be set aside for fraud if the judgment debtor raises a prima facie case — the court will then try the fraud allegation."},
  {id:187,number:"Dicey Ill. 4 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — violence and threats",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-146] (Ill. 4) · Jet Holdings Inc v Patel [1990] 1 Q.B. 335 (CA)",question:"A & Co sue X in California to recover sums allegedly misappropriated by X. X defends the proceedings on the ground that representatives of A & Co had been violent towards him and that X had, under further threats from them, paid substantial amounts to A & Co. X is too frightened to attend depositions in California, and judgment in default is given against him. A & Co's lawyers represent to the Californian court that X's account of violence and threats is untrue. X has an arguable defence that the judgment was obtained by fraud. What order should the English court make?",answer:"X has an arguable defence that the judgment was obtained by fraud, and leave to defend is given. The use of violence and threats to prevent a party from participating in foreign proceedings, combined with misrepresentation to the foreign court that the account of such conduct is untrue, is capable of constituting fraud in the procurement of the judgment.",keyPrinciple:"Violence, threats, and intimidation that prevent a party from defending foreign proceedings, combined with misrepresentation to the foreign court, may constitute fraud impeaching the judgment."},
  {id:188,number:"Dicey Ill. 5 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — re-litigation and estoppel",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-147] (Ill. 5) · House of Spring Gardens Ltd v Waite [1991] 1 Q.B. 241 (CA)",question:"A & Co sue X, Y and Z in Ireland for misuse of confidential information and breach of copyright, and obtain judgment for £3 million. X, Y and Z appeal unsuccessfully to the Supreme Court of Ireland. X and Y (but not Z) bring a fresh action in Ireland to set aside the judgment on the ground of fraud. After a lengthy trial, the allegation of fraud is rejected. The original judgment is sought to be enforced in England. Is it enforceable against all three defendants? Is Z estopped from alleging fraud?",answer:"The original judgment is enforceable in England, not only against X and Y (who re-litigated the fraud issue and lost), but also against Z. Z is estopped from alleging fraud even though he did not join the Irish proceedings to set aside the judgment: he is privy to the second Irish judgment because the original judgment was obtained against X, Y and Z jointly and severally, and because he was well aware of the proceedings to set aside the original judgment.",keyPrinciple:"A defendant who is privy to co-defendants' unsuccessful fraud challenge in the foreign court may be estopped from re-raising the fraud defence in English enforcement proceedings."},
  {id:189,number:"Dicey Ill. 6 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — perjury and forgery tried afresh",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-147] (Ill. 6) · Owens Bank Ltd v Bracco [1992] 2 A.C. 443",question:"A foreign court gives judgment for A against X. X had argued that A's evidence was perjured and based on falsified documents. The defence is rejected at trial and also on appeal. When A seeks to enforce the judgment in England, is the court bound to accept the foreign court's finding on the fraud issue?",answer:"No. The English court is not bound to recognise the decision of the foreign court on perjury and forgery. If the evidence put forward by X appears to raise a prima facie case of fraud, the English court may try for itself the allegation of fraud raised by X. This is the distinctive feature of the English fraud defence: it permits re-examination of fraud allegations even where those allegations have been considered and rejected by the foreign court.",keyPrinciple:"The English court may re-examine a fraud allegation even where the foreign court has already considered and rejected it, provided the defendant raises a prima facie case."},
  {id:190,number:"Dicey Ill. 7 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — appellate judgment obtained by fraud",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-147] (Ill. 7) · cf. Merchant International Co Ltd v Natsionalna Aktsionerna Kompaniia Naftogaz [2012] EWCA Civ 196",question:"A foreign court gives judgment for A against B, but on appeal by B the judgment at first instance is set aside. A contends that the judgment of the appeal court was obtained by fraud and is not entitled to recognition in England. If A's contention succeeds, what is the consequence?",answer:"A's contention is liable to succeed. If the appellate judgment was obtained by fraud, it will be denied recognition in England. The consequence is that the judgment of the first instance court — which was set aside by the tainted appellate judgment — may be recognised and enforced in England. The fraud defence operates to strip the appellate judgment of recognition, thereby reviving the underlying first instance judgment.",keyPrinciple:"If a foreign appellate judgment is denied recognition for fraud, the first instance judgment it purported to set aside may itself be recognised and enforced in England."},
  {id:191,number:"Dicey Ill. 8 (Fraud)",subtopic:"Fraud — in rem proceedings and conspiracy",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 53 [14-147] (Ill. 8) · Castrique v Behrens (1861) 30 L.J.Q.B. 163",question:"B is the owner of a British ship. He mortgages her to A and later goes bankrupt. While the ship is at Melbourne, M, the master, draws a bill of exchange on B for necessaries supplied to the ship by X. The bill is never accepted and is dishonoured at maturity. During the ship's return voyage to Europe, X conspires with Y, and indorses the bill to Y (but not for value) in order that Y may take advantage of a foreign law provision whereby the bona fide holder of such a bill can take proceedings in rem against the ship in the foreign court. When the ship is in the foreign port, Y brings proceedings in rem resulting in the court ordering the sale of the ship in order to pay the bill. In an action by A against X in England for conspiracy to defraud, can A impeach the foreign judgment for fraud?",answer:"No. A cannot impeach the foreign judgment for fraud in the conspiracy action in England. Although X and Y conspired, the foreign judgment in rem ordered the sale of the ship and was given by a court of competent jurisdiction. The judgment in rem has disposed of the property and cannot be impeached collaterally in separate proceedings for conspiracy.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment in rem ordering the sale of property may not be collaterally impeached for fraud in English proceedings for conspiracy to defraud."},
  {id:192,number:"Dicey Ill. 1 (Public Policy)",subtopic:"Illegality of underlying contract",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 54 [14-157] (Ill. 1) · Lenkor Energy Trading DMCC v Puri [2021] EWCA Civ 770",question:"A and X enter into a contract under which A agrees to pay X for the illegal transportation of goods from one State to another. The goods are delivered and payment is made to an intermediary, Y, but not passed on to X. X sues Y and obtains a judgment from a foreign court. Is the judgment enforceable in England?",answer:"Yes. The judgment is enforceable, notwithstanding the illegality of the underlying contract. The public policy defence is narrowly applied: enforcement of the judgment does not require the English court itself to give effect to the illegal contract. The judgment is a distinct obligation from the underlying transaction, and the circumstances do not meet the high threshold for refusing enforcement on public policy grounds.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment is enforceable notwithstanding illegality in the underlying transaction — the public policy defence against enforcement is narrow and exceptional."},
  {id:193,number:"Dicey Ill. 2 (Public Policy)",subtopic:"Foreign judgment refusing to recognise English judgment",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 54 [14-157] (Ill. 2) · ED&F Man (Sugar) Ltd v Haryanto (No.2) [1991] 1 Lloyd's Rep. 429 (CA)",question:"A & Co sell sugar to X, an Indonesian citizen, for $200 million under contracts governed by English law. Disputes arise and X seeks a declaration in England that he is not bound. His action is dismissed, and the judgment is confirmed by the Court of Appeal. Further English proceedings result in X agreeing to pay A & Co $27 million. Subsequently, X commences proceedings in Indonesia against A & Co, and the Indonesian court decides that the settlement agreement is illegal because it arises out of illegal contracts, and that it is contrary to Indonesian public policy to recognise the English judgment. A & Co seek a declaration in England that the settlement agreement is valid and binding on X. Is the Indonesian judgment recognised?",answer:"No. The Indonesian judgment is not recognised because the real issue in those proceedings — the validity of the underlying agreements — had already been the subject of a decision of the English court. The Indonesian court's characterisation of the contracts as illegal and its refusal to recognise the English judgment on public policy grounds does not bind the English court. Where the substance of the dispute has already been determined by an English court, a subsequent foreign judgment refusing to recognise that determination will not itself be recognised.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment which refuses to recognise an English judgment on the same underlying dispute will not itself be recognised in England — the English determination prevails."},
  {id:194,number:"Dicey Ill. 3 (Public Policy)",subtopic:"ECHR — flagrant breach",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 54 [14-157] (Ill. 3) · Government of USA v Montgomery (No.2) [2004] UKHL 37",question:"Proceedings are brought against X in the United States. A default judgment is awarded in circumstances which would not satisfy the requirements of Art. 6 of the European Convention on Human Rights (if that Convention were directly applicable). Is the judgment nevertheless enforceable in England?",answer:"It appears that the judgment may nevertheless be enforced in England, unless the breach of the European Convention standards in the US proceedings is 'flagrant'. The ECHR does not apply directly to US proceedings, but Art. 6 standards inform English public policy. Only a flagrant breach of Art. 6 — not a mere departure from Convention standards — will justify refusing enforcement on public policy grounds.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign judgment from a non-Convention State may be refused enforcement on public policy grounds only where the procedural deficiency amounts to a 'flagrant' breach of Art. 6 ECHR standards."},
  {id:195,number:"Dicey Ill. 1 (Natural Justice)",subtopic:"No notice of proceedings — common law",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 55 [14-167] (Ill. 1) · Copin v Adamson (1875) 1 Ex.D. 17 (CA)",question:"X, who was resident in England, held shares in a French company. The articles of association provided that all disputes between the company and its shareholders should be subject to the jurisdiction of the French courts and that service of process on each shareholder should be at a designated address in France. The company went into liquidation and A brought an action in France against X for moneys not paid up on X's shares. Process was served on X at the designated address, but X received no notice of the proceedings. The French court gave judgment against X before 1937 (when the 1933 Act was extended to France). A brought an action on the judgment against X in England. Was the judgment impeachable?",answer:"No. The judgment was not impeachable at common law. Although X received no actual notice of the proceedings, service was effected in the manner specified in the articles of association to which X had agreed by subscribing for shares. At common law, Rule 55 (natural justice) did not require actual notice where the defendant had agreed to a particular mode of service and that mode was duly followed.",keyPrinciple:"At common law, a foreign judgment is not impeachable for breach of natural justice where the defendant agreed to a particular mode of service and that mode was duly followed, even if the defendant received no actual notice."},
  {id:196,number:"Dicey Ill. 2 (Natural Justice)",subtopic:"No notice of proceedings — 1933 Act",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 55 [14-167] (Ill. 2) · 1933 Act, s.4(1)(a)(iii)",question:"The circumstances are the same as the previous illustration (French company shares, no actual notice), except that the French judgment was given after 1937 and A registered the judgment in England under the 1933 Act. Should the registration be set aside?",answer:"Yes. Registration would be set aside. Under the 1933 Act, s.4(1)(a)(iii), registration of a foreign judgment must be set aside if the judgment debtor, being the defendant in the original proceedings, did not (notwithstanding that process may have been duly served on him in accordance with the law of the foreign court) receive notice of those proceedings in sufficient time to enable him to defend them. The 1933 Act imposes a higher standard than the common law — actual notice in sufficient time is required.",keyPrinciple:"Under the 1933 Act, registration must be set aside if the defendant did not receive actual notice in sufficient time to defend, even where process was duly served under the foreign court's law."},
  {id:197,number:"Dicey Ill. 3 (Natural Justice)",subtopic:"Biased and unfair proceedings",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 55 [14-168] (Ill. 3) · Jacobson v Frachon (1927) 138 L.T. 386 (CA)",question:"X, a merchant of Lyons, contracted to sell silk to A, a merchant of London. A dispute having arisen about the quality of the silk, X brought an action against A in a court at Lyons. The court appointed an expert to examine the goods and report on their quality. The expert made no proper examination; he refused to listen to A's witnesses; and his report (described by the English court as 'the erroneous and uncandid production of a biased and prejudiced mind') was wholly in favour of X. The French court gave judgment in favour of X. When A sued X in England, X pleaded the French judgment as a defence. Was the judgment impeachable?",answer:"No. The judgment was not impeachable because the French court was not obliged to accept the report, and because A attacked it unsuccessfully in France. The biased report of the expert did not amount to a breach of natural justice by the court itself. The proceedings in France gave A an opportunity to challenge the report, which A took but failed to make good.",keyPrinciple:"A biased expert report does not render a foreign judgment impeachable for breach of natural justice where the foreign court was not obliged to accept the report and the aggrieved party had an opportunity to challenge it."},
  {id:198,number:"Dicey Ill. 4 (Natural Justice)",subtopic:"Default judgment without any hearing",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 55 [14-168] (Ill. 4) · Adams v Cape Industries Plc [1990] Ch. 433 (CA)",question:"206 claimants sue X & Co and Y & Co, both English companies, in an action for personal injuries in the Federal Court in Texas. X & Co and Y & Co, not wishing to submit to the jurisdiction of the US court, take no part in the proceedings. X & Co and Y & Co are given notice of a hearing to assess damages in default of appearance, but again take no part. On the application of the claimants, the US judge signs a default judgment for $15 million, but without holding any hearing. No evidence of damage or injury to the claimants is placed before the judge; the judgment is signed before the judge has an opportunity to consider the medical records or summaries of each claimant's case; the damages awarded are quantified on a global basis or as an average per claimant, and are arbitrary. Is the judgment enforceable?",answer:"No. The judgment is not enforceable. The entry of a default judgment for $15 million without any hearing, without evidence of damage or injury, and with damages quantified arbitrarily on a global or per-claimant average basis, constitutes a breach of natural justice (or substantive justice) under Rule 55. Even where a defendant chooses not to appear, the foreign court must follow a procedure that meets minimum standards of due process.",keyPrinciple:"A default judgment entered without any hearing and without evidence of the claimants' losses, with damages assessed arbitrarily, is unenforceable for breach of natural justice."},
  {id:199,number:"Dicey Ill. 5 (Natural Justice)",subtopic:"Opportunity to appeal — procedural failure",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Dicey Illustration"],flags:[],reference:"Dicey Rule 55 [14-168] (Ill. 5) · Agbara v Shell Petroleum Development Company of Nigeria Ltd [2019] EWHC 3340 (QB)",question:"In proceedings in Nigeria brought against A, the court denies A the opportunity to present its case in defence. A has the opportunity to appeal, but the appeal fails because it does not comply with the required procedures. May A nevertheless rely on the breach of natural justice to resist enforcement of the judgment in England?",answer:"Yes. A may nevertheless rely on the breach of natural justice to resist enforcement of the judgment in England. The right to appeal does not cure the original breach of natural justice at the trial level. A procedural failure in the appeal (failure to comply with required procedures) does not amount to a waiver of the natural justice objection, particularly where the breach at trial deprived A of the fundamental right to present its defence.",keyPrinciple:"A breach of natural justice at trial is not cured by the availability of an appeal, and a procedural failure in the appeal process does not waive the right to resist enforcement on natural justice grounds."},
  {id:200,number:"FJ-C1",subtopic:"Theoretical basis for enforcement",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Principle"],flags:[],reference:"Williams v Jones (1845); Godard v Gray (1870); Adams v Cape [1990]; Rubin v Eurofinance [2013] 1 AC 236",question:"What is the theoretical basis for the enforcement of foreign judgments at common law, and which two alternative bases have been rejected (and in which cases)?",answer:"The obligation doctrine: a foreign judgment creates a legal obligation to pay a debt, enforceable by action. The claimant sues on the obligation, not the underlying contract (Williams v Jones; Godard v Gray). Reciprocity was rejected in Schibsby and confirmed in Adams v Cape. Comity was rejected in Adams v Cape. Lord Collins in Eurofinance called the obligation basis 'purely theoretical' but confirmed it remains the doctrinal basis.",keyPrinciple:"Enforcement rests on the obligation doctrine — not on comity or reciprocity."},
  {id:201,number:"FJ-C2",subtopic:"Error of law — no review on the merits",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Godard v Gray (1870) LR 6 QB 139",question:"A foreign court applies the governing law incorrectly — even making an obvious mistake of English law. Can the judgment be impeached for error?",answer:"No. A foreign judgment cannot be impeached for error of fact or law. The obligation to pay the debt is what matters. If judgments were impeachable for error, enforcement would become an effective retrial: Godard v Gray.",keyPrinciple:"Error of fact or law — however obvious — is no ground for refusing enforcement."},
  {id:202,number:"FJ-C3",subtopic:"Final and conclusive — reopenable judgment",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Nouvion v Freeman (1889) 15 App. Cas. 1",question:"A foreign judgment is given in a multi-phase procedure where the first phase can be reopened by the same court in a later phase. Is it final and conclusive?",answer:"No. A judgment liable to be reopened or varied by the same court is not final and conclusive. English law sets what 'final and conclusive' means; foreign law determines whether the judgment has attained res judicata effect: Nouvion v Freeman.",keyPrinciple:"A judgment that can be reopened by the court that gave it is not final — finality is an English-law concept applied to the foreign judgment's status."},
  {id:203,number:"FJ-C4",subtopic:"Pending appeal — still final",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Nouvion v Freeman (1889) 15 App. Cas. 1; Colt Industries v Sarlie (No 2) [1966] 1 WLR 1287",question:"Is a foreign judgment still final and conclusive while subject to appeal to a higher court?",answer:"Yes. A judgment subject to appeal to a higher court remains final — only the possibility of review by the same court negates finality. The enforcing court may impose conditions pending the appeal: Nouvion v Freeman; Colt v Sarlie.",keyPrinciple:"Appeal to a higher court does not negate finality — only reopening by the same court does."},
  {id:204,number:"FJ-C5",subtopic:"Default judgment — obligation basis",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Schibsby v Westenholz (1870) LR 6 QB 155",question:"D, living in England with no connection to a foreign country and no notice of proceedings, has a default judgment entered against him there. Is it enforceable?",answer:"No. A default judgment is unenforceable where D was not present in the foreign country and did not submit. Jurisdiction under the foreign court's own municipal law is irrelevant — only jurisdiction in the 'international sense' matters: Schibsby v Westenholz.",keyPrinciple:"A default judgment against a non-present, non-submitting defendant is unenforceable — the foreign court's own jurisdictional rules are irrelevant."},
  {id:205,number:"FJ-C6",subtopic:"Procedural irregularity — irrelevant",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Pemberton v Hughes [1899] 1 Ch 781 (CA)",question:"Can a foreign judgment be refused recognition because of an irregularity in service of process under the foreign court's own procedural rules?",answer:"No. Only jurisdiction in the international sense matters — not compliance with the foreign court's own procedural rules. Irregularity of procedure is no bar to recognition unless it offends English views of substantial justice: Pemberton v Hughes.",keyPrinciple:"Procedural irregularity under foreign law is irrelevant — only international jurisdiction and English standards of substantial justice matter."},
  {id:206,number:"FJ-C7",subtopic:"Corporate presence — the test",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Adams v Cape Industries Plc [1990] Ch. 433 (CA)",question:"What is the test for determining whether a company is 'present' in a foreign jurisdiction for recognition and enforcement purposes?",answer:"A company is present only where: (1) it has a fixed place of business and carries on its own business there for more than a minimal period ('branch office'); or (2) a representative carries on the company's business (not the representative's own) from a fixed place of business. A subsidiary carrying on its own business does not make the parent present. Authority to contract is a powerful indicator but not conclusive: Adams v Cape.",keyPrinciple:"Presence requires a fixed place of business or a representative carrying on the company's (not the agent's own) business from such a place."},
  {id:207,number:"FJ-C8",subtopic:"Natural persons — physical presence",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Adams v Cape Industries Plc [1990] Ch. 433 (CA); Schibsby v Westenholz (1870)",question:"What is the presence requirement for a natural person and is fleeting presence sufficient?",answer:"Physical presence in the foreign country at the time of service is required. It does not matter if D owns land there, is a national, committed a tort there, or breached a contract there. Fleeting or transient presence suffices: Adams v Cape (confirming Colt v Sarlie). Whether residence without presence suffices was left open in Adams v Cape.",keyPrinciple:"Natural persons must be physically present — fleeting presence suffices, but residence without presence remains undecided."},
  {id:208,number:"FJ-C9",subtopic:"Default judgment — natural justice",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Adams v Cape Industries Plc [1990] Ch. 433 (CA)",question:"A foreign court enters a default judgment without holding any hearing, without evidence of damage, and with damages assessed arbitrarily on a global average. Is it enforceable?",answer:"No. A default judgment entered without judicial assessment of the evidence of damage, with damages quantified arbitrarily, is contrary to English views of substantial justice. Good faith does not cure the deficiency: Adams v Cape.",keyPrinciple:"A default judgment without any judicial assessment of damages offends natural justice and is unenforceable."},
  {id:209,number:"FJ-C10",subtopic:"Defensive merits argument",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"State Bank of India v Murjani [1991] (unreported, CA)",question:"D argues the merits in a foreign court while also contesting jurisdiction. Has D submitted?",answer:"Not necessarily. Arguing the merits defensively does not automatically amount to submission, provided D maintains the jurisdiction objection and does not invite a merits determination. Consider: could D have asked for severance? Was D required by local procedure to argue merits? Did D indicate arguments were without prejudice to jurisdiction? Did D invite the court to deal with the merits? State Bank of India v Murjani.",keyPrinciple:"Defensive merits argument is not automatic submission if the jurisdiction objection is maintained and D does not invite a merits ruling."},
  {id:210,number:"FJ-C11",subtopic:"Scope of voluntary submission",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Murthy v Sivajothi [1999] 1 WLR 467 (CA)",question:"If a defendant voluntarily submits to the jurisdiction of a foreign court in one claim, does that submission extend to other claims in the same proceedings?",answer:"Yes — submission extends to other claims concerning the same or related subject matter. It does not extend to claims by strangers or unrelated matters. Whether a claim is 'related' is a question of fact and degree: Murthy v Sivajothi.",keyPrinciple:"Voluntary submission extends to related claims in the same proceedings but not to unrelated claims or claims by strangers."},
  {id:211,number:"FJ-C12",subtopic:"Submission by conduct — the test",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Rubin v Eurofinance [2012] UKSC 46, [2013] 1 AC 236",question:"What is the test for determining whether a party has submitted to a foreign court's jurisdiction by its conduct?",answer:"Submission is inferred from conduct inconsistent with maintaining a jurisdiction objection. Ask: would this step have had any rational purpose if the party were still contesting jurisdiction? Characterisation of submission is a question of English law; the foreign court's view is relevant but not determinative: Rubin v Eurofinance.",keyPrinciple:"Submission = conduct inconsistent with maintaining a jurisdiction objection, tested by asking whether the step had any rational purpose if jurisdiction were still contested."},
  {id:212,number:"FJ-C13",subtopic:"Insolvency — no special exception",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Rubin v Eurofinance [2012] UKSC 46; Cambridge Gas v Navigator Holdings [2007] 1 AC 508 (overruled)",question:"Is there a special exception to the Dicey jurisdictional requirements for foreign insolvency proceedings?",answer:"No. Cambridge Gas (which held that insolvency is a collective process and the normal Dicey rules do not apply) was overruled in Eurofinance. There is no special insolvency exception — the collective nature of proceedings is not a substitute for jurisdictional competence. However, a creditor who files a proof of debt in a foreign administration submits to the supervising court's general insolvency jurisdiction.",keyPrinciple:"No special insolvency exception to the Dicey jurisdictional requirements — Cambridge Gas was overruled."},
  {id:213,number:"FJ-C14",subtopic:"Implied agreement to submit",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Vizcaya Partners Ltd v Picard [2016] UKPC 5",question:"Can an agreement to submit to a foreign court's jurisdiction be implied from choice of law, place of contracting, or place of performance?",answer:"No. An agreement to submit can be implied but it must be an actual agreement. Choice of law, place of contracting, and place of performance do not by themselves suffice. Whether an implied agreement exists is governed by the law applicable to the contract. An implied submission may also be limited in scope — e.g., a consumer contract submission does not extend to statutory avoidance claims: Vizcaya v Picard.",keyPrinciple:"Implied submission requires actual agreement — choice of law, place of contracting, and place of performance are insufficient by themselves."},
  {id:214,number:"FJ-C15",subtopic:"s 33 CJJA — protected purposes",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Henry v Geoprosco [1976] QB 726 (reversed by CJJA 1982, s 33)",question:"D appears in a foreign court solely to contest jurisdiction and seek a stay. Has D submitted?",answer:"No. CJJA s 33 provides that appearing (conditionally or otherwise) for protected purposes does not constitute submission. Protected purposes: (a) contesting jurisdiction; (b) asking for dismissal/stay for arbitration or another forum; (c) obtaining release of seized property. This reversed Geoprosco, which had held that a conditional appearance to contest service amounted to submission.",keyPrinciple:"CJJA s 33 protects appearances to contest jurisdiction, seek a stay, or recover seized property — reversing Geoprosco."},
  {id:215,number:"FJ-C16",subtopic:"Unnecessary merits pleading = submission",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Marc Rich & Co AG v Società Italiana Impianti PA (No 2) [1992] 1 Lloyd's Rep 624 (CA)",question:"D contests jurisdiction in a foreign court, loses at the highest level, then files a fresh merits defence without any reservation as to jurisdiction. Has D submitted?",answer:"Yes. If you plead the merits when doing so is unnecessary to preserve a jurisdictional challenge, you submit. Once you submit, you lose the s 32 shield: Marc Rich v Impianti (No 2).",keyPrinciple:"Pleading the merits when unnecessary to preserve a jurisdiction challenge is unequivocal submission — and submission in the interlocutory phase covers the whole proceeding."},
  {id:216,number:"FJ-C17",subtopic:"Compelled participation — no submission",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"AES Ust-Kamenogorsk [2013] UKSC 35; Harada v Turner [2003] EWCA Civ 1695",question:"D loses a jurisdiction challenge in a foreign court and is compelled by local procedure to continue litigating on the merits. Has D submitted?",answer:"No. If D is compelled to participate and continues to protest jurisdiction throughout, there is no submission — D has no real choice but to continue. A party forced to engage 'in the teeth of all its objections' does not submit: AES (affirming Harada).",keyPrinciple:"Compelled participation after losing a jurisdiction challenge is not submission if the defendant maintains its objection throughout."},
  {id:217,number:"FJ-C18",subtopic:"s 32 — foreign court's finding on arbitration clause",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"AES Ust-Kamenogorsk [2013] UKSC 35; Spliethoff's v Bank of China [2015] EWHC 999 (Comm)",question:"A foreign court finds that an arbitration or jurisdiction agreement is invalid under its domestic law. Is the English court bound by that finding?",answer:"No. Under CJJA s 32, the English court independently determines the validity and applicability of the agreement. The foreign court's finding is irrelevant: AES. Section 32 is a binary shield: non-submission bars recognition absolutely; submission loses it entirely. There is no residual discretion (rejecting Rix LJ's obiter in AES): Spliethoff's v Bank of China.",keyPrinciple:"The English court independently determines the validity of jurisdiction/arbitration agreements — s 32 is binary with no residual discretion."},
  {id:218,number:"FJ-C19",subtopic:"Substance over formalities — local procedure",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Ecobank Transnational Inc v Tanoh [2015] EWCA Civ 1309",question:"Under local procedure, D is required to plead both jurisdiction and merits simultaneously — failure to plead the merits would be treated as conceding the claim. D does so, expressly reserving its jurisdictional objection. Has D submitted?",answer:"No. Substance over formalities: do not ask whether there was a merits pleading — ask what its purpose was. Where the absence of a merits pleading equals concession under local procedure, filing one is protective, not submission: Ecobank v Tanoh.",keyPrinciple:"Filing a merits pleading required by local procedure to avoid concession is protective, not submission — substance over formalities."},
  {id:219,number:"FJ-C20",subtopic:"Fraud — re-examination despite foreign rejection",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Abouloff v Oppenheimer (1882) 10 QBD 295 (CA)",question:"A foreign court investigates an allegation of fraud and rejects it. Can the English court re-examine the fraud issue when enforcement is sought?",answer:"Yes. A foreign judgment obtained by fraud is impeachable even where the fraud was considered and rejected by the foreign court. Brett LJ's 'different question' device: the foreign court asked 'what are the facts?'; the English court asks 'was the court misled?' — two different actions, no estoppel. Fraud must be distinguished from error: the court is misled (fraud) vs mistaken (error) — only the former vitiates: Abouloff v Oppenheimer.",keyPrinciple:"The English court may re-examine fraud even where the foreign court rejected it — Brett LJ's 'different question' device avoids estoppel."},
  {id:220,number:"FJ-C21",subtopic:"Fraud — cause of action vs collateral",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Jet Holdings Inc v Patel [1990] 1 QB 335 (CA)",question:"Does it matter whether fraud alleged against a foreign judgment goes to the cause of action or is merely collateral to it?",answer:"No. It does not matter whether the fraud goes to the cause of action or is collateral — both are grounds for impeachment. Retrial of the fraud issue in England is a feature, not a bug — 'litigants should try the action where they expect to enforce': Jet Holdings v Patel (affirming Abouloff).",keyPrinciple:"Fraud impeaches a foreign judgment whether it goes to the cause of action or is merely collateral."},
  {id:221,number:"FJ-C22",subtopic:"Fraud — no fresh evidence required (foreign)",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Owens Bank Ltd v Bracco [1992] 2 AC 443 (HL)",question:"When raising the fraud defence against a foreign judgment, must the defendant adduce fresh evidence not before the foreign court?",answer:"No. The same evidence that was before the foreign court can be used. The HL declined to overrule Abouloff. Lord Templeman acknowledged a 'very strong case' for reform but held it is a matter for Parliament — especially now the rule is incorporated in the 1920 Act: Owens Bank v Bracco.",keyPrinciple:"No fresh evidence is required to raise fraud against a foreign judgment — the same evidence rejected by the foreign court may be re-examined."},
  {id:222,number:"FJ-C23",subtopic:"Fraud — second set of proceedings bars re-litigation",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"House of Spring Gardens Ltd v Waite [1991] 1 QB 241 (CA)",question:"D alleges fraud in the original foreign proceedings (rejected). D then commences a separate action in the foreign court to set aside the judgment for fraud — that too is dismissed. Can D raise fraud again in English enforcement proceedings?",answer:"No. Where fraud is litigated and rejected in a separate second set of foreign proceedings, issue estoppel prevents re-alleging it in England. The debtor's election to return to the foreign court carries weight. This also binds co-defendants who were aware of the second proceedings and let others fight on their behalf: House of Spring Gardens v Waite. Distinguished from Abouloff/Jet Holdings, where fraud was raised only within the original proceedings.",keyPrinciple:"Fraud litigated and rejected in a separate second set of foreign proceedings cannot be re-raised in England — the debtor's election to re-litigate abroad carries weight."},
  {id:223,number:"FJ-C24",subtopic:"Fraud — contextual approach",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"AK Investment CJSC v Kyrgyz Mobil Tel Ltd [2011] UKPC 7 at [116]",question:"What alternative framework for the fraud defence was proposed by Lord Collins in his obiter in AK Investment, and what are its three variables?",answer:"Lord Collins proposed replacing the blanket Abouloff rule with a contextual, case-by-case approach calibrated to: (a) the reliability of the foreign legal system; (b) the scope for challenge in the foreign forum; (c) the type of fraud alleged. Where the system is reliable and remedies available, greater weight to the foreign court's determination; where unreliable or no remedies, re-examination is more readily justified.",keyPrinciple:"Lord Collins [116]: a contextual approach calibrated to reliability of the foreign court, scope for challenge, and type of fraud alleged."},
  {id:224,number:"FJ-C25",subtopic:"Fraud — domestic fresh evidence rule",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Takhar v Gracefield Developments Ltd [2019] UKSC 13",question:"What is the domestic rule for setting aside a judgment for fraud, and must the party alleging fraud have exercised due diligence?",answer:"Domestic: fresh evidence is required, but no obligation to have conducted due diligence. Evidence must be new (not in the party's possession at trial) but need not have been undiscoverable by reasonable diligence — 'a knave does not escape liability because he is dealing with a fool.' Exception (Lords Kerr/Sumption): where the claimant deliberately chose not to investigate: Takhar v Gracefield. Significance for foreign judgments: demolishes the assumption that domestic law was stricter than Abouloff.",keyPrinciple:"Domestic fraud rule: fresh evidence required but no due diligence obligation — demolishing the assumption that domestic law was stricter than Abouloff."},
  {id:225,number:"FJ-C26",subtopic:"Fraud — retrenchment from Takhar",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Finzi v Jamaican Redevelopment Foundation Inc [2023] UKPC 39",question:"A party seeks to set aside a judgment for fraud, relying on evidence it had for 12 months before concluding a settlement agreement. Must it explain why the evidence was not used earlier?",answer:"Yes. If relying on evidence not adduced originally, the party must show it is new or explain why it was not deployed — 'a good reason' is required. Reopening settled claims with pre-existing material rebranded as fraud evidence risks abusive re-litigation. Briggs describes this as a 'measure of retrenchment' from Takhar: Finzi.",keyPrinciple:"Evidence deployed to allege fraud must be genuinely new, or the party must explain why it was withheld — pre-existing material rebranded as fraud evidence is abusive."},
  {id:226,number:"FJ-C27",subtopic:"Art 6 ECHR — foreign set-aside",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Merchant International Co Ltd v NAK Naftogaz [2012] EWCA Civ 196",question:"A foreign court sets aside its own judgment on 'newly discovered circumstances' without a full rehearing and without considering whether the evidence was previously available. Must England recognise the set-aside?",answer:"No. The English court may refuse to recognise a foreign set-aside judgment that breaches Art 6 ECHR. A judgment debt is a 'possession'; removing it without procedural fairness breaches legal certainty. HRA s 6 requires the English court (as a public authority) not to act incompatibly with Convention rights: Merchant International v Naftogaz.",keyPrinciple:"A foreign set-aside judgment that breaches Art 6 ECHR standards of legal certainty may be refused recognition — a judgment debt is a 'possession.'"},
  {id:227,number:"FJ-C28",subtopic:"PTIA s 5 — severable causes of action",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Lewis v Eliades [2003] EWCA Civ 1758",question:"A composite foreign judgment awards both treble damages on one cause of action and ordinary compensatory damages on a separate cause of action. Can the compensatory cause of action be enforced?",answer:"Yes. Where a composite judgment has distinct, severable causes of action and the multiple damages apply only to some, the remainder can be enforced: Lewis v Eliades. Left open: whether the compensatory base within a multiplied award is itself recoverable.",keyPrinciple:"Severable non-multiplied causes of action within a composite judgment remain enforceable — but the compensatory base within a multiplied award was left open."},
  {id:228,number:"FJ-C29",subtopic:"PTIA s 5 — total bar including compensatory base",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Motorola Solutions Inc v Hytera Communications Corp Ltd [2025] EWCA Civ 1667",question:"Can a claimant enforce just the compensatory element of a foreign damages award where the total sum was arrived at by trebling?",answer:"No. PTIA s 5 bars the entire multiple damages award — including the compensatory base and ancillary costs. You cannot enforce just the compensatory element if the sum was 'arrived at by the process of multiplication': Motorola v Hytera (resolving the issue left open in Lewis v Eliades).",keyPrinciple:"s 5 PTIA bars the entire multiplied award including the compensatory base — no part of a sum arrived at by multiplication is recoverable."},
  {id:229,number:"FJ-C30",subtopic:"Anti-enforcement injunctions — English assets",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"SAS Institute Inc v World Programming Ltd [2020] EWCA Civ 599",question:"A foreign judgment not recognised in England — can the judgment creditor reach assets situated in England through orders of the foreign court?",answer:"No. A foreign judgment not recognised in England cannot reach English assets. Enforcement against locally situated assets is a matter for the English court alone. An anti-enforcement injunction will protect English assets but will not restrain enforcement against assets within the foreign court's reach. A refusal to enforce is a substantive determination, not merely procedural: SAS Institute v World Programming.",keyPrinciple:"An unrecognised foreign judgment cannot reach English assets — enforcement against local assets is for the English court alone."},
  {id:230,number:"FJ-C31",subtopic:"Anti-enforcement injunctions — requirements",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Principle"],flags:[],reference:"SAS Institute [2020]; Bank St Petersburg [2020]; Ecobank [2015]; Yeo, 'Anti-Enforcement Injunctions' (2021)",question:"When will an English court grant an anti-enforcement injunction restraining enforcement of a foreign judgment, and what are the main grounds of refusal?",answer:"AEIs are granted: (1) to protect English assets from unrecognised foreign judgments (SAS); (2) to enforce a negative obligation not to enforce (e.g., settlement agreement: Bank St Petersburg). Same criteria as ASIs; 'exceptional circumstances' required — in practice, most applications fail for delay (Ecobank; Sun Travels). Where there is a primary negative obligation, comity is reduced; where the injunction remedies a prior breach, comity is heavier (Yeo).",keyPrinciple:"AEIs require exceptional circumstances and follow ASI criteria — delay is usually fatal and comity concerns intensify as proceedings progress."},
  {id:231,number:"FJ-C32",subtopic:"Issue estoppel — jurisdictional decision as 'merits'",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"The Sennar (No 2) [1985] 1 WLR 490 (HL)",question:"A foreign court declines jurisdiction, holding that an exclusive jurisdiction clause binds the claimant. Can that decision ground an issue estoppel preventing the claimant from relitigating the point in England?",answer:"Yes. A foreign court's decision to decline jurisdiction can be a 'merits' judgment for estoppel purposes if it substantively determined the parties' contractual rights (here, the scope and applicability of the EJC). Estoppel arises regardless of whether the English court would criticise the foreign reasoning: The Sennar (No 2).",keyPrinciple:"A jurisdictional determination can found an issue estoppel where it substantively determined the parties' contractual rights."},
  {id:232,number:"FJ-C33",subtopic:"Issue estoppel — procedural judgments",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Desert Sun Loan Corp v Hill [1996] 2 All ER 847 (CA)",question:"Can a procedural or interlocutory judgment of a foreign court ground an issue estoppel in England?",answer:"In principle, yes (Evans and Stuart-Smith LJJ). But the exact issue must have been raised and clearly decided, and the defendant must have expressly submitted the specific issue to the foreign court. Caution is required — it is difficult to know whether a foreign procedural decision is truly final. Roch LJ dissented: a foreign court's finding on its own jurisdiction can never be conclusive — it would 'pull itself up by its own bootstraps': Desert Sun v Hill.",keyPrinciple:"A procedural foreign judgment can in principle found an issue estoppel, but only where the specific issue was raised, clearly decided, and truly final."},
  {id:233,number:"FJ-C34",subtopic:"CJJA s 34 — same cause of action",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:[],reference:"Republic of India v India Steamship Co Ltd (The Indian Grace) (No 2) [1998] AC 878 (HL)",question:"Can a claimant bring a fresh action in England on a different legal theory where the underlying events have already been determined by a foreign court?",answer:"No. CJJA s 34 bars proceedings on a cause of action already determined abroad. Claims arising from the same event are barred even under different legal theories — one shipment, one voyage, one fire = one cause of action. However, s 34 is a personal procedural defence capable of waiver by conduct (e.g., agreeing to English jurisdiction, participating in English steps): The Indian Grace.",keyPrinciple:"s 34 bars re-litigation of the same cause of action even under different legal theories — but it is a personal defence capable of waiver."},
  {id:234,number:"FJ-C35",subtopic:"Issue estoppel — requirements",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Principle"],flags:[],reference:"The Sennar (No 2) [1985]; Desert Sun v Hill [1996]; Carl Zeiss Stiftung [1967]",question:"What four conditions must be met for an issue estoppel to arise from a foreign judgment?",answer:"(1) A foreign court of competent jurisdiction rendered a final and conclusive judgment on the merits. (2) The parties are the same (or privies). (3) The issues are identical — the exact issue must have been raised and clearly decided. (4) The decision was necessary to the ruling, not merely collateral (cannot be obiter). Carl Zeiss caution: it would be unfair to estop a defendant in England for not defending a trivial foreign claim.",keyPrinciple:"Issue estoppel requires: competent court, final judgment on the merits, same parties, identical issue, and necessity of the decision."},
  {id:235,number:"FJ-S1",subtopic:"Jurisdictional competence — corporate presence",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Adams v Cape Industries [1990] Ch. 433; Dicey Rule 47, First Case",question:"MegaCorp (English) appoints LocalCo (independently owned Nigerian company) as its exclusive sales agent. LocalCo operates from its own Lagos office, uses its own stationery, and solicits orders forwarded to MegaCorp for acceptance — it has no authority to conclude contracts. A Nigerian customer obtains judgment against MegaCorp in Nigeria. MegaCorp took no part. Is the judgment enforceable?",answer:"No. LocalCo is carrying on its own business, not MegaCorp's. No authority to bind MegaCorp, no reimbursement of costs, independent premises and staff. MegaCorp is not 'present' in Nigeria: Adams v Cape.",keyPrinciple:"An independently owned distributor without authority to bind the overseas corporation does not establish its presence."},
  {id:236,number:"FJ-S2",subtopic:"Submission — Eurofinance test",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Eurofinance [2013]; Ecobank [2015]; AES [2013]; Marc Rich [1992]; CJJA ss 32–33",question:"EngCo is sued in Country X. The contract has a London arbitration clause. EngCo challenges jurisdiction; Country X's procedure requires a simultaneous 'preliminary merits response' or concession. EngCo files both, expressly 'without prejudice to jurisdiction.' The challenge fails on appeal. EngCo continues to file merits defences under protest. Judgment is given. Has EngCo submitted?",answer:"No. (1) The merits response was required by local procedure and filed without prejudice — protective, not submission (Ecobank). (2) Continued participation after losing the challenge, under protest throughout — compelled, not voluntary (AES/Harada). (3) EngCo never invited a merits ruling without reservation (distinguishing Marc Rich). Under s 32, the English court independently determines the arbitration clause's validity.",keyPrinciple:"Protective merits pleading required by local procedure + continued participation under protest = no submission."},
  {id:237,number:"FJ-S3",subtopic:"Fraud — fresh evidence and estoppel",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Abouloff (1882); House of Spring Gardens [1991]; Owens Bank [1992]; AK Investment [2011] at [116]",question:"A obtains judgment against X in Country Z for $5m. X alleges fraud in those proceedings — rejected by the Country Z court. X does not commence any separate set-aside proceedings. A seeks enforcement in England. X raises the fraud defence using the same evidence. Can X succeed?",answer:"Yes, under current law. Abouloff + Owens Bank: no fresh evidence required; same evidence may be re-examined. House of Spring Gardens distinguished: estoppel arises only from a second, separate set of proceedings — here fraud was raised only within the original proceedings. Under Lord Collins's proposed reform (AK Investment [116]), the outcome might differ depending on the reliability of Country Z's courts and the remedies available there.",keyPrinciple:"Fraud rejected in the same proceedings can be re-examined in England without fresh evidence — estoppel only arises from a separate second set of foreign proceedings."},
  {id:238,number:"FJ-S4",subtopic:"Multiple damages — severability",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"Lewis v Eliades [2004]; Motorola v Hytera [2025]; PTIA 1980, s 5",question:"A US court awards: (a) $10m in compensatory damages for trade secret misappropriation, trebled to $30m; (b) a separate $2m compensatory award for breach of a software licence (no multiplier). Which parts are enforceable in England?",answer:"(a) The $30m is wholly unenforceable — s 5 PTIA bars the entire multiplied award including the compensatory base (Motorola v Hytera). (b) The $2m is enforceable — a separate, severable cause of action not subject to any multiplier (Lewis v Eliades). The key distinction: compensatory base within a multiplied award (unenforceable) vs independently assessed compensatory cause of action (enforceable).",keyPrinciple:"The compensatory base within a multiplied award is barred; a separately assessed compensatory cause of action is enforceable if severable."},
  {id:239,number:"FJ-S5",subtopic:"Issue estoppel and s 32",tags:["topic:Foreign Judgments","type:Case"],flags:["ai-scenario"],reference:"The Sennar [1985]; AES [2013]; Spliethoff's [2015]; CJJA ss 32–33",question:"ShipCo (English) charters a vessel to CargoCo under a charterparty with a London arbitration clause. CargoCo sues in Country Y; ShipCo challenges jurisdiction citing the arbitration clause. The Country Y court holds the clause inapplicable. ShipCo does not participate further; judgment enters. CargoCo seeks enforcement; argues ShipCo is estopped. Who is right?",answer:"ShipCo. (1) s 32 bars recognition: proceedings brought in breach of an arbitration agreement, D did not submit (s 33 protects the jurisdictional challenge). s 32 is binary — no discretion (Spliethoff's). (2) The Country Y court's finding on the arbitration clause does not bind the English court (AES). (3) CargoCo's estoppel argument fails: the English court will not recognise the finding of a court whose judgment it is bound to refuse under s 32.",keyPrinciple:"Where s 32 bars recognition, the foreign court's finding on the arbitration clause cannot bind England or found an estoppel."},
];

